WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.560
[Amit Varma]: I often say that we make sense of the world by joining dots and the more dots

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:15.000
[Amit Varma]: we have, the clearer our picture of the world. So how do we gather these dots? The

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.120
[Amit Varma]: immediate experiences of our own lives will never add up to enough and we need

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:23.120
[Amit Varma]: to have the humility to recognize this. We need to make an effort to learn about

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:26.960
[Amit Varma]: the world, to see the world through the eyes of others, many others, so that we

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:32.240
[Amit Varma]: can enrich our own understanding. For me, the best way to gather these dots is by

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:36.320
[Amit Varma]: reading books. If you read a lot and your reading is both broad and deep, your

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:40.160
[Amit Varma]: vision is that much more likely to be sharper and clearer. And this is also

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:45.600
[Amit Varma]: true if we have an appreciation of data. What is data but a gathering of dots,

00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:49.600
[Amit Varma]: facts about the world that we can bring together to paint a picture in high

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:53.960
[Amit Varma]: definition. Our brains have evolved to prefer stories over numbers, especially

00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:58.040
[Amit Varma]: large numbers and complex statistics, which is why so many of the best

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:01.760
[Amit Varma]: storytellers are those who have a sense of the bigger picture. And more

00:01:01.760 --> 00:01:07.800
[Amit Varma]: importantly, who actively look at the data to seek out the bigger picture.

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:14.680
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:20.120
[Unknown]: behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:25.720
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Rukmini S, a pioneering

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:29.640
[Amit Varma]: data journalist who learned her chops at the Times of India and was the first

00:01:29.640 --> 00:01:34.280
[Amit Varma]: data editor at the Hindu. She has written for a series of major publications across

00:01:34.280 --> 00:01:38.760
[Amit Varma]: the world. And I'm a bit uncertain about the term data journalist, as I consider

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:43.480
[Amit Varma]: Rukmini an outstanding journalist who also happens to understand and use data

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:48.120
[Amit Varma]: very well, as indeed every journalist should. A few months ago, as this pandemic

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:52.680
[Amit Varma]: got underway, Rukmini started up a groundbreaking podcast called The Moving

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:57.560
[Amit Varma]: Curve, in which she explored her own intellectual curiosity about the pandemic.

00:01:57.560 --> 00:02:02.120
[Amit Varma]: Every day, she would ask a question about the unfolding crisis and try to answer

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:06.600
[Amit Varma]: it by examining the research out there, looking at the data and so on. Every

00:02:06.600 --> 00:02:11.000
[Amit Varma]: episode was five to 10 minutes long, and she recently hit 100 episodes of The

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.920
[Amit Varma]: Moving Curve. I've been planning to ask her on the show for a long time now, and

00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:19.480
[Amit Varma]: was delighted when we could finally make it happen. Before we begin with our

00:02:19.480 --> 00:02:45.240
[Amit Varma]: episode, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

