[Amit Varma]: and much interactivity. It costs rupees 10,000 or $150. You can check out the

00:02:55.960 --> 00:03:00.920
[Amit Varma]: details at IndiaUncut.com slash clear writing. This link will be in the show

00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:04.120
[Amit Varma]: notes. If you want to bridge the gap between the thoughts in your head and the

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:09.400
[Amit Varma]: words on the page, then the art of clear writing might be just what you need.

00:03:09.400 --> 00:03:13.960
[Amit Varma]: November batches begin on Saturday, November 7. So hurry and register before

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:22.040
[Amit Varma]: then. IndiaUncut.com slash clear writing.

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:23.720
[Amit Varma]: Look, really welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:29.720
[Guest]: Thank you. It's so exciting to be here. I feel a bit like a T20 player who's

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:35.880
[Guest]: walked into a test match, except that you actually can get the T20 numbers. So

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:37.640
[Guest]: that's not a good analogy either.

00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:42.760
[Amit Varma]: No, no, it's not a bad analogy, because there are T20 players who walked into a

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:46.520
[Amit Varma]: test match and completely owned that feel like David Warner, for example, the

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:49.880
[Amit Varma]: first time, you know, he played for the Delhi franchise back in the day, his

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:52.920
[Amit Varma]: teammate Virender Sehwag told him that, you know, you have a game for test

00:03:52.920 --> 00:03:56.200
[Amit Varma]: cricket. And that sounded very counterintuitive, because Warner was a bit

00:03:56.200 --> 00:03:59.240
[Amit Varma]: of a basher there. But look what happened. He's one of the great players, Steve

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:04.200
[Amit Varma]: Smith, Jaspreet Bumrah. So and I just have to say that I am just an unabashed

00:04:04.200 --> 00:04:07.560
[Amit Varma]: admirer of your podcast, The Moving Curve and the things that you've done with it.

00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:10.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, I don't think I would be able to do something like that. But that kind

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:14.760
[Amit Varma]: of regularity, asking important questions and all of that. But before we kind of

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:19.160
[Amit Varma]: embarrass each other with too much praise, let's, let's move on. I'm very curious to

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:23.480
[Amit Varma]: know about your background. Because, you know, in our minds as often and you know,

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:27.320
[Amit Varma]: when you hear the words, data journalist, which for some reason is how people kind

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:30.680
[Amit Varma]: of refer to you, though, I think that's not I mean, you're obviously just a very

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:34.760
[Amit Varma]: good journalist period. And, you know, but and one of the things that obviously

00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:40.040
[Amit Varma]: strikes me about your background is that you were a sort of a hardcore reporter or

00:04:40.040 --> 00:04:44.120
[Amit Varma]: regular journalist who was reporting stories and doing all of that. But I'd say

00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:47.800
[Amit Varma]: take me even before that, take me to your childhood, what kind of person were you?

00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:52.600
[Amit Varma]: What kind of career did you look at? How did you get attracted to journalism and why?

00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:59.320
[Guest]: Right. So I do think that anyone who knew me growing up would be quite surprised by

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:04.680
[Guest]: this turn, because I never really demonstrated any particular affinity for math,

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:10.600
[Guest]: though I enjoyed it in school. So I grew up in Pune, my parents there, I am very much a

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:18.360
[Guest]: Punekar in most ways. I left home after I did a BA in psychology at Ferguson College for

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:23.640
[Guest]: reasons that I could not tell you anymore. You know, one of those things that you drift

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:30.040
[Guest]: into when you're 18. I enjoyed it. I do feel like it exposed me to statistics and

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:34.840
[Guest]: experimental science for the first time. So that was interesting. But somewhere in the

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:39.080
[Guest]: back of my mind, I always knew that what I was going to get into was some form of writing.

00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:43.880
[Guest]: I don't think I knew anything about how journalism worked, but that seemed like the

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:50.280
[Guest]: sort of thing that people who like to write did. So I went to, you know, from Pune, the

00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:55.560
[Guest]: Asian College of Journalism in Chennai was very far, very expensive at the time. The more

00:05:55.560 --> 00:06:04.760
[Guest]: well-known and familiar yet well-regarded option was the Sophia Polytechnic in Mumbai.

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:10.600
[Guest]: So what I did is I did a postgraduate diploma in social communications media. That's the

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:18.920
[Guest]: mouthful that that course is called. And I loved it. It's women's only college, 30 students

00:06:18.920 --> 00:06:23.960
[Guest]: living in a hostel for the first time, very political place and with very specific

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:28.120
[Guest]: political ideas. And, you know, I'm sure we'll talk about that later, because one of the

00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:33.080
[Guest]: things that that I spend a lot of time thinking about and thinking about how journalism can

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:40.280
[Guest]: get better about is about how to be less polarised. And I wouldn't say that that

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:49.800
[Guest]: that wasn't polarised too. It was sort of like being, I suppose, on a mini GNU sort of equivalent

00:06:49.800 --> 00:06:54.040
[Guest]: then. But yeah, again, none of this is a criticism of the course, which I absolutely loved.

00:06:54.920 --> 00:07:01.800
[Guest]: P Sainath was one of our teachers. He's someone I hugely admire and love very much. He's

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:08.760
[Guest]: family for me a bit now. So that was the first time I read nonfiction. That was the first

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:12.840
[Guest]: time I read newspapers regularly. That was the first time I felt engaged with any sort of

00:07:13.560 --> 00:07:18.920
[Guest]: political thinking at all. I was very much one of those persons who floated through

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:23.960
[Guest]: undergraduate college, building wonderful personal relationships, falling in love,

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:29.480
[Guest]: joining a rock band and having the rest of the world entirely pass me by. So,

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:35.720
[Guest]: so far it was when I woke up. And I'm very much one of those people who's everything,

00:07:35.720 --> 00:07:40.520
[Guest]: politically awakening, learning, everything happened on this job since I sort of sleepwalked

00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:45.640
[Guest]: through college in that respect. I loved it. I think I did well. And immediately after,

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:52.280
[Guest]: it was a one year course. Immediately after that, there were some campus placements and I started

00:07:52.280 --> 00:07:58.120
[Guest]: an internship at the times of India and Bombay. And I ended up working there for four years in

00:07:58.120 --> 00:08:04.920
[Guest]: all. And that was, as you mentioned, very much regular journalism. So the first few months was

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:12.360
[Guest]: very much, you were the person who was, you were the spot boy. You were sent to run for everything,

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:16.840
[Guest]: any press release, any event. You never knew what your day was like. Anything that was in the

00:08:16.840 --> 00:08:22.040
[Guest]: furthest possible suburb, you were likely to be sent there. You know, an experience that nothing

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:27.240
[Guest]: else will give you. Just knowing the local train system in and out, knowing every suburb in and

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:32.280
[Guest]: out. So I did that. Then I covered the education beat for a little while. And the last beat that I

00:08:32.280 --> 00:08:37.960
[Guest]: covered in Mumbai was state government. In the course of news reporting, I ended up doing a bit

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:44.600
[Guest]: of crime reporting and got very interested in legal reporting because of some trials that I

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:50.520
[Guest]: ended up covering quite regularly, although I wasn't a court journalist. And then after that,

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:57.160
[Guest]: after I did that for four years, I went to the School of Oriental and African Studies in London

00:08:57.160 --> 00:09:02.280
[Guest]: to do a Master's in Development Studies. So that again, in that respect, was a sort of

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:10.760
[Guest]: standard lefty program. I enjoyed it, but I was also very sure that I immediately wanted to get

00:09:10.760 --> 00:09:17.320
[Guest]: back to Indian journalism that, you know, I really felt that that that was the most productive use

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:24.600
[Guest]: of my time. I was really hungry to come back and work. Around that time, or a little before that,

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:31.000
[Guest]: the Times of India had set up in Delhi, a group called the Times Insight Group, which is a small

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:39.160
[Guest]: team of reporters focused on data journalism. So, you know, I think most people don't associate the

00:09:39.160 --> 00:09:44.520
[Guest]: Times of India with data journalism, but that really is the first place that set up a systematic

00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:52.280
[Guest]: team to do this. So Jaideep Bose, the editor then and now who had hired me in Bombay, when I came

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:57.720
[Guest]: back, I talked to him about things that I could do, and he mentioned this team. Because one of

00:09:57.720 --> 00:10:03.000
[Guest]: the things that had happened is when I was doing my Master's, I felt I was reading World Bank

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.440
[Guest]: reports for the first time, you know, it's not that they hadn't existed on the internet, I had

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:12.120
[Guest]: just not known anything about it. And I felt that there was so much research that I was reading,

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:16.920
[Guest]: that I should have been incorporating into news stories. So it wasn't yet data as such, it was

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:21.800
[Guest]: more the feeling that there's rigorous research and academic work that I should be incorporating

00:10:21.800 --> 00:10:28.360
[Guest]: into news reporting. And then it was really three years of learning on the job. I joined that team

00:10:28.360 --> 00:10:34.520
[Guest]: in Delhi, I moved to Delhi, I got to do a whole lot of very sort of straight place data journalism,

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:40.040
[Guest]: which is, NSS has put out a report today, report about it. World Bank has put this report out,

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:44.440
[Guest]: reported it. I'm really glad I got to do that. And really on data work, I was starting from

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:49.720
[Guest]: learning how to do addition and subtraction in an Excel sheet, I hadn't done anything of that

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:56.520
[Guest]: sort before. And that group is headed still by Shankar Agaraman, who's a, you know, old school

00:10:56.520 --> 00:11:04.920
[Guest]: financial journalist, very well known among the old school Delhi journalists, a great boss,

00:11:06.360 --> 00:11:10.760
[Guest]: someone who really shines on election and budget days in particular. And again, this is not

00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:16.840
[Guest]: something people give the Times of India credit for, but it truly does shine on election days,

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:23.400
[Guest]: especially. And the other great thing I got to do then was travel. There was there was nothing

00:11:24.760 --> 00:11:30.760
[Guest]: that no one said no to me for any idea I had, you know, around then in 2009. And then food

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:35.960
[Guest]: prices started escalating the price of daal, all of that started escalating. So I could write about

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:40.760
[Guest]: it and look at the numbers and do all of that, but then also go to Bundelkhand and report on it.

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:45.000
[Guest]: And these were just things off the top of my head, I wanted to do the Bihar elections,

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.640
[Guest]: because it seemed like development indicators had really improved in Mitesh's first term,

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:54.840
[Guest]: I got to go and cover the Bihar elections, I wanted to write on the panchayat system,

00:11:54.840 --> 00:11:59.960
[Guest]: because I could see that there was incremental change going on in political representation there.

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:05.400
[Guest]: So I got to cover Rajasthan's panchayat elections. Similarly, what political representation I got to

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:09.480
[Guest]: report from Nagaland, where there has never been a woman MLA and I got to, you know,

00:12:09.480 --> 00:12:16.520
[Guest]: trail two women candidates as they went campaigning. So that that I really I remember

00:12:17.480 --> 00:12:24.200
[Guest]: feeling then that I was getting paid to understand the country. And just nothing I could have asked

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:34.280
[Guest]: for better than that. I did feel like I was maybe getting a bit slow and maybe a bit lazy,

00:12:34.280 --> 00:12:39.240
[Guest]: you know, spending too much time unproductively staring at the screen sometimes in office. So

00:12:39.240 --> 00:12:44.200
[Guest]: I'm glad then that Siddharth Vaidhyarajan, now the Wire's editor, then the Hindu's editor got

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:50.120
[Guest]: in touch with me because I do think I was stagnating a bit then. He hired me to the Hindu

00:12:50.120 --> 00:12:56.200
[Guest]: in 2013. And I was there for three years. And after Siddharth left and Malini Parthasarathy

00:12:56.200 --> 00:13:04.440
[Guest]: took over, she made me the data editor then, which was the first Indian publication to have a data

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:12.120
[Guest]: editor position. So both Siddharth and Malini did have that vision for that vision, that focus,

00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:20.600
[Guest]: that emphasis on data over there. So that was the last sort of mainstream media full time job I had.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:27.160
[Guest]: In 2016, I quit the Hindu, I worked for the Huff Post for a little while doing similar work.

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:35.480
[Guest]: And since 2018, I've been doing this independently. And I moved to Chennai in 2016.

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:40.600
[Amit Varma]: So the lesson for this for people listening, by the way, is that good Indian podcasters come out

00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:47.480
[Amit Varma]: of Ferguson College Pune because I also graduated from there. Yeah, I passed out in 94. So I think

00:13:47.480 --> 00:13:52.760
[Amit Varma]: that might have been a little before your time. Yeah. So what did you do in a rock band?

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:57.560
[Guest]: I sang. Oh, wow. Amazing. Are there videos on YouTube that we can embarrass you with?

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:03.160
[Guest]: There are pictures from Pune times that my parents can embarrass me with.

00:14:04.120 --> 00:14:07.400
[Amit Varma]: Wow, instantly 1000s of listeners immediately try to Google and

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:13.720
[Amit Varma]: figure that out. What I find very interesting about this whole narrative, and this is something

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:19.160
[Amit Varma]: that I've been thinking about for a while now, is the distinction between the abstract and the

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:22.840
[Amit Varma]: the abstract and the concrete in people's experiences. Like it strikes me that when you go

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:26.760
[Amit Varma]: to college, or when you go to whatever academic thing you do, you're being taught abstract ideas,

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:30.920
[Amit Varma]: you're being taught abstractions about the world. And then at some point, of course, if you remain

00:14:30.920 --> 00:14:35.640
[Amit Varma]: in academics, you can just remain in that abstract realm forever. But if you go out in the real world,

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:41.240
[Amit Varma]: and you actually, you know, engage with it, then you get exposed to concrete realities. And it

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:45.560
[Amit Varma]: seems to me that this distinction between abstraction and reality is something that

00:14:45.560 --> 00:14:49.480
[Amit Varma]: can possibly apply to journalists like you in many ways, like first, you do the journalistic

00:14:49.480 --> 00:14:53.800
[Amit Varma]: training and all of that, and then you're out in the real world, you're reporting from the weeds.

00:14:53.800 --> 00:14:58.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's one sort of element of it. Another element of it is just how you engage with data,

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:03.240
[Amit Varma]: like, you know, many people would and we'll, of course, explore this later in the episode in more

00:15:03.240 --> 00:15:07.720
[Amit Varma]: detail. But people will often bring their own biases to data and try to make it conform to

00:15:07.720 --> 00:15:12.280
[Amit Varma]: the narratives. But to do that, you really have to understand the data intuitively and all that.

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:16.760
[Amit Varma]: And like you said, it strikes me that it might actually have been a feature and not a bug that

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:21.080
[Amit Varma]: you had to learn all that from scratch how to add and subtract in Excel, for example, which I still

00:15:21.080 --> 00:15:26.040
[Amit Varma]: don't know. And, you know, which would have also given you a concrete sense of data and its

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:31.240
[Amit Varma]: limitations and what it can be used for. Is there something kind of to that, like, as you engage

00:15:31.240 --> 00:15:36.200
[Amit Varma]: more and more concretely with India, are your old frames sort of collapsing and new frames taking

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:40.040
[Amit Varma]: their place? Is there a journey like that, that you sort of consciously thought about?

00:15:40.040 --> 00:15:44.040
[Guest]: Yeah, you've absolutely hit the nail on the head, because that is what has been my process for the

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:50.200
[Guest]: last five years. So I would say that I still have, you know, largely left of center politics and

00:15:50.200 --> 00:15:55.960
[Guest]: ideas. But one of the big things which has really come through both the points that you mentioned

00:15:55.960 --> 00:16:01.880
[Guest]: simultaneously, which is one part of it is through reporting directly and part of it is going with

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:06.280
[Guest]: the data. You know, it didn't even come as a moment of reckoning that I felt that I was,

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:11.240
[Guest]: you know, confronting all that I believed or held dear and that it was all withering away.

00:16:11.240 --> 00:16:17.640
[Guest]: I suppose it had been happening continuously and didn't really come as a surprise to me,

00:16:17.640 --> 00:16:23.960
[Guest]: these realizations. But yes, accepting that a lot of what the left in India in particular holds

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:30.680
[Guest]: true and passes on through universities or even through leftist academics and the journalists who

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:36.840
[Guest]: faithfully report everything that they say is deceptive, it's problematic, it's not doing anyone

00:16:36.840 --> 00:16:43.960
[Guest]: much good. So, you know, all of this sounds a bit quaint, all this UPA era stuff is now very quaint

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:47.880
[Guest]: that we were having all these intense discussions about things like the public distribution system,

00:16:47.880 --> 00:16:54.680
[Guest]: but that's what we were discussing back then. So I think, you know, things like accepting that,

00:16:54.680 --> 00:17:00.600
[Guest]: you know, holding the public distribution system as a model for something that must be upheld

00:17:00.600 --> 00:17:06.920
[Guest]: at every cost and anything that's seen as an alternative like cash or a universal basic

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:12.840
[Guest]: income must be sort of reflexively attacked is something that I had to unlearn. And I'm,

00:17:12.840 --> 00:17:17.880
[Guest]: you know, happy to have been able to do that. And I consistently find that the data and research

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:24.440
[Guest]: continues to back these things up. The other thing, all sort of mass publicly provided goods

00:17:24.440 --> 00:17:29.720
[Guest]: that I remain, you know, firm supporter of in the middle of a pandemic, the importance of

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:35.160
[Guest]: affordable, accessible public health, it's there for everyone to see. But to go on talking about

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:41.640
[Guest]: these things as, but we must strengthen public schools, but we must strengthen the public health

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:50.120
[Guest]: system without accepting how discriminatory and demeaning it can be to have to be entangled with

00:17:50.120 --> 00:17:56.600
[Guest]: it is privilege, is ultimately privilege. So the economist Jishnu Das is someone whose work

00:17:56.600 --> 00:18:02.760
[Guest]: I admire very much. And I like engaging with because it makes me rethink things that I might

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:08.600
[Guest]: have gone in thinking of a certain way. And I think his work on healthcare has been one of those

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:13.880
[Guest]: things that I really feel I wish a lot of journalism students would look at and read because

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:21.080
[Guest]: things like accepting that an MBBS doctor in a public hospital necessarily cares more and provides

00:18:21.080 --> 00:18:28.760
[Guest]: better care, gives better prescriptions even than quack in a private clinic is something we would

00:18:28.760 --> 00:18:32.840
[Guest]: all assume and something we would all, you know, put our weight behind, but he's consistently shown

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:39.320
[Guest]: that not to be the case, you know, good, solid research in both urban and rural settings in

00:18:39.320 --> 00:18:48.040
[Guest]: Madhya Pradesh and Delhi. I feel in 2012 and 2013, these are things that I was confronting. And at

00:18:48.040 --> 00:18:52.440
[Guest]: that time, it felt like a debate with two sides. But now I see there are a number of people who

00:18:52.440 --> 00:18:58.040
[Guest]: sort of, you know, exist in the middle and don't see these as choices. But as let's all start with

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:03.720
[Guest]: the belief that care or education should be something that is available to everybody, but at

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:10.200
[Guest]: their own, with their own agency, with their own self-respect alive, you know. So yeah, I think

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:15.720
[Guest]: both reporting and dealing with the data has made me rethink many of those things. And when you talk

00:19:15.720 --> 00:19:23.560
[Guest]: about the value, if any, in having to do everything longhand in the hard way, it really is true. It

00:19:23.560 --> 00:19:29.080
[Guest]: sounds like some, you know, some fuddy-duddy thing that your dad says, right, which is that you'll

00:19:29.080 --> 00:19:35.880
[Guest]: only know it when you write it out by hand, but you will only figure it out when you've done some

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:42.760
[Guest]: data stuff manually is something that I've just had to accept. There's a lot of, you know, I'm

00:19:42.760 --> 00:19:48.920
[Guest]: sure we'll talk about this in a bit, but I spend a shocking amount of my time doing work manually.

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:53.320
[Guest]: And this isn't a humble brag. If I had better skills, I wouldn't be doing this manually. It's

00:19:53.320 --> 00:19:57.800
[Guest]: a colossal waste of time. And anyone who's building their skills right now should build skills so that

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:02.040
[Guest]: they're not doing what I'm doing. This is not smart. But there are, you know, every time I think,

00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:08.360
[Guest]: I was just thinking when I go on Amit's podcast, maybe I should put out an appeal to people,

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:16.120
[Guest]: to anyone who wants to do this work for me, you know, paid for credit, that I need developers.

00:20:16.120 --> 00:20:20.760
[Guest]: Now that I don't work in a newsroom anymore, I can't hire a developer and I don't earn enough

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:25.240
[Guest]: to like hire a full time developer for myself. So I said, you know, this sort of geeky person,

00:20:25.240 --> 00:20:31.240
[Guest]: if they listen to the show, I should put this up. But it's not just not letting go of control,

00:20:31.240 --> 00:20:38.040
[Guest]: which is a problem. But it also is that reading so much of this stuff manually gives me insights

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:44.200
[Guest]: that I wouldn't miss otherwise. So just to give you an example, I've really enjoyed engaging with

00:20:44.200 --> 00:20:49.880
[Guest]: legal data. And while this sounds like something that I'm doing that's complicated or with great

00:20:49.880 --> 00:20:54.120
[Guest]: skills, but a lot of it is just reading court judgments. Again, if there were good machine

00:20:54.120 --> 00:20:58.600
[Guest]: learning tools, I'm sure people could reduce the sort of donkey work they put into it. But a lot of

00:20:58.600 --> 00:21:03.240
[Guest]: what I do is just reading a lot of court judgments. So there was a point at which I was

00:21:03.240 --> 00:21:09.080
[Guest]: having to manually read Metropolitan Magistrate Court rulings in Mumbai, because I was looking

00:21:09.080 --> 00:21:13.640
[Guest]: actually for sexual assault cases for something specific I was working on. But while I was

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:18.360
[Guest]: looking for this, I ended up noticing that on the daily sort of docket of most judges,

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:25.240
[Guest]: there was a large number of cases of particular IPC section, and I was couldn't really understand

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:31.160
[Guest]: why it was coming up that often. Then, when I looked at the section, it was causing hurt using

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:36.040
[Guest]: a poisonous substance. And I couldn't for the life of me figure out why I was seeing so many every

00:21:36.040 --> 00:21:40.920
[Guest]: day. Most Metropolitan Magistrates were seeing many of these cases every day. And then I started

00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:45.880
[Guest]: noticing that they were all acquittals, all acquittals. So I just couldn't figure out what

00:21:45.880 --> 00:21:51.400
[Guest]: was going on. So what I ended up getting to the bottom of, and then I ended up investigating and

00:21:51.400 --> 00:21:57.640
[Guest]: writing about that separately, was that at that time, the drug mephedrone, which was called

00:21:57.640 --> 00:22:05.160
[Guest]: Meow Meow on the street, was not in the NDPS, the India's Narcotics Act. It wasn't in the schedule

00:22:05.160 --> 00:22:12.760
[Guest]: that gives cops the powers to go after it in those ways. So the only IPC section that they felt

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:19.240
[Guest]: they could use to catch this peddlers was this one. But it's completely the wrong section,

00:22:19.240 --> 00:22:25.640
[Guest]: because it requires you to not just prove possession at that moment, but also intend to

00:22:25.640 --> 00:22:32.600
[Guest]: cause hurt, which a peddler doesn't have. So it was one of the most common cases that

00:22:32.600 --> 00:22:36.600
[Guest]: Metropolitan Magistrates were looking at. And it had a 100% acquittal rate.

00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:44.760
[Guest]: Yeah, it's the seen and the unseen. I was just thinking about that, that this is what I saw.

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:49.000
[Guest]: And this is the entire world of things behind it. I ended up going to Mumbai for it and speaking to

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:53.320
[Guest]: the NDPS person and, you know, a couple of ACPs as well. And they were all like,

00:22:53.320 --> 00:22:58.200
[Guest]: yes, we know that it wasn't the right one to use, sorry, but there's nothing we could do about it.

00:22:58.200 --> 00:23:03.000
[Guest]: And the judges were so sick of these cases coming to them, because in each one they had to say,

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:08.280
[Guest]: you haven't shown intent to hurt, acquit, acquit, acquit. And the cops were also using it to do a

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:13.640
[Guest]: bit of, you know, petty score settling. And there were people who'd been in jail without bail for a

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:20.200
[Guest]: year, I found, you know, the disproportionately high number of Muslim men in it. So there was

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:25.000
[Amit Varma]: all of that going on. No, it's so fascinating. I mean, it's almost like you're a forensic detective

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:28.760
[Amit Varma]: and you're going through the data to figure all this out. No, I read in one of your interviews

00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:33.320
[Amit Varma]: about how you mentioned that, possibly during this case that you had like these hundreds of

00:23:33.320 --> 00:23:38.280
[Amit Varma]: tabs open, and you're manually going through one judgment at a time. And that's just incredible.

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:44.280
[Amit Varma]: So I actually second your appeal. And if there are listeners of the show who can create solutions for

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:48.760
[Amit Varma]: this, whether at scale or whether at an individual level, please do get in touch with Rukmini.

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:53.880
[Amit Varma]: Another part of your sort of personal journey, which you also, I think, referred to

00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:58.680
[Amit Varma]: in one of your interviews as being interesting and affecting your perspective was moving away

00:23:58.680 --> 00:24:04.440
[Amit Varma]: from Delhi, shifting to Chennai, having kids, choosing to kind of be located there. Did that

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:09.480
[Amit Varma]: also like shift your frame of reference and make you, you know, take you out of that Delhi journalism

00:24:09.480 --> 00:24:15.240
[Guest]: bubble, so to say, and make you look at things differently? It did. But the more I think about it,

00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:21.080
[Guest]: the more I want to make sure that I don't start looking back at that experience as something

00:24:21.640 --> 00:24:27.800
[Guest]: frothy and silly and, you know, full of narcissistic people who only talk about each

00:24:27.800 --> 00:24:35.240
[Guest]: other's work. There is that too. But that's not all of Delhi's journalism. And to everyone who

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:41.640
[Guest]: wants to continue in, at least in public policy journalism, I would highly recommend working in

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:47.320
[Guest]: Delhi for a while. I feel like the journalism I'm able to do now, and in all sorts of ways,

00:24:47.320 --> 00:24:54.520
[Guest]: even personally, is because I was in Delhi for those key years in between. Moving away from

00:24:54.520 --> 00:25:00.680
[Guest]: Delhi has, it's made me more conscious of how it's impossible to understand some of the things that

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:06.600
[Guest]: matter so deeply to people from a particular part of the country, not just from Delhi, but from

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:13.400
[Guest]: anywhere else. So being in Chennai, I feel like I could see the media trying to make sense and

00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:19.000
[Guest]: grapple with this jallikattu issue when it happened a few years ago. I still sense it when they try to

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:25.160
[Guest]: write about NEET, the medical entrance exam and, you know, Tamil Nadu's feelings on it. And I just

00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:32.120
[Guest]: realized how lost in translation this stuff is. Things like self-respect are impossible to, are

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:38.440
[Guest]: impossible to communicate through journalism sometimes. And it underpins so much of what goes

00:25:38.440 --> 00:25:46.120
[Guest]: on in Tamil Nadu in particular. So, you know, I think while a lot of people who move away from

00:25:46.120 --> 00:25:53.000
[Guest]: Delhi or even people who talk self-deprecatingly about being in Delhi diminish it a fair bit,

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:59.720
[Guest]: I do think that it's possible to move away and write, you know, more considered stuff only after

00:25:59.720 --> 00:26:06.360
[Guest]: you've actually been there first. So I'm very happy for, I loved Delhi. I loved living there.

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:11.880
[Guest]: I loved working in journalism there. And, you know, the conversations I had and the arguments

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:17.560
[Guest]: over public policy, over politics, you know, over dinner and people's houses on terraces,

00:26:18.840 --> 00:26:23.560
[Guest]: they were very formative. And I still, they are the sort of contours of the debates and

00:26:23.560 --> 00:26:31.560
[Guest]: discussions I'm still having in a sense. Having kids, yeah, that now that's a big change in

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:39.400
[Guest]: multiple ways. I mean, one of it is just the time part of it. So it just means that there's a

00:26:39.400 --> 00:26:44.600
[Guest]: significant shift in the type of journalism I do because of the hours in the day I have.

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:52.840
[Guest]: It's also definitely changed my consumption diet of journalism. My, I mean, some of it is just,

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:58.360
[Guest]: it sounds so silly and childish to say, but I know that a lot of parents feel this is that I can't

00:26:58.360 --> 00:27:06.360
[Guest]: consume violence much at all. I'm someone who's always pushed back against things like trigger

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:11.960
[Guest]: warnings. And I still would a bit in journalism. I mean, I'm sorry, not in an entertainment show,

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:18.680
[Guest]: but even in journalism, I have no, I cannot consume violence anymore. And also, I mean,

00:27:18.680 --> 00:27:24.280
[Guest]: it really came home to me in the pandemic that I no longer can keep up with things on a sort of

00:27:24.280 --> 00:27:30.440
[Guest]: minute to minute basis anymore, which then means that my need to distill information both for

00:27:30.440 --> 00:27:37.240
[Guest]: myself and then for people who read me or listen to me has now become a part of my journalism.

00:27:37.240 --> 00:27:43.880
[Guest]: Because it really is that the only time that I really can think at length about the world is

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:49.240
[Guest]: sort of at the end of the day. And I'm glad that I'm not reacting to events immediately,

00:27:49.240 --> 00:27:57.320
[Guest]: and that I have had a few hours of considered time to think about it. So it's a luxury, but

00:27:58.280 --> 00:28:02.040
[Guest]: I'm glad that I'm able to do that sort of work. Now, the thing about journalism is

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:08.120
[Guest]: across the board, and definitely I see this about data journalism teams in newsrooms is that

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:13.640
[Guest]: you're sort of expected to do a bit of everything, which is you have to put out the daily NSSO,

00:28:13.640 --> 00:28:18.360
[Guest]: put out this report sort of thing too, as well as the well-considered longer things.

00:28:18.360 --> 00:28:24.360
[Guest]: And that just leaves very little space to think. Yeah, and I mean, it was surprising to me,

00:28:25.080 --> 00:28:30.120
[Guest]: it made me very happy. And it was surprising to me that especially during the pandemic,

00:28:30.120 --> 00:28:34.760
[Guest]: when people were home and so much more housework, so much more childcare,

00:28:34.760 --> 00:28:40.040
[Guest]: other people were suddenly consuming news in a similar sort of way. And then that feeling of,

00:28:40.040 --> 00:28:43.400
[Guest]: especially in the beginning of the pandemic, I mean, it's hard to remember it now, but we were

00:28:43.400 --> 00:28:47.800
[Guest]: starting from figuring out, is this a virus or a bacteria? How do these things work? Does it

00:28:47.800 --> 00:28:53.480
[Guest]: move through coughing? So it suddenly felt that, wow, it's nine o'clock and I just check the news.

00:28:53.480 --> 00:28:58.760
[Guest]: And okay, now we know for the first time that it isn't mutating, or something huge and significant

00:28:58.760 --> 00:29:05.240
[Guest]: had happened. So I think other people too were feeling that need, that I can't follow

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:10.440
[Guest]: ball by ball commentary of this. I need to know by the end of the day what happens.

00:29:10.440 --> 00:29:14.280
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, a couple of tangential questions, which I hadn't planned to ask, but they came up

00:29:14.280 --> 00:29:19.720
[Amit Varma]: from, you know, what you were just saying. And question number one is, you know, writers often

00:29:19.720 --> 00:29:24.680
[Amit Varma]: talk about how when they become writers, the quality of their reading changes,

00:29:24.680 --> 00:29:29.560
[Amit Varma]: they start reading differently. Earlier, they are sort of reading whatever books they are just,

00:29:29.560 --> 00:29:33.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, they're just going with the story or whatever. But when they become writers themselves,

00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:38.280
[Amit Varma]: they start noticing nuanced aspects of the craft and all of that. Now, you spoke a little earlier

00:29:38.280 --> 00:29:42.360
[Amit Varma]: about the consumption diet changing as you had your kids and you had responsibilities at home

00:29:42.360 --> 00:29:46.760
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, the way you consumed it changed from a real time thing where, you know, people

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:50.920
[Amit Varma]: might be tracking everything on Twitter all the time and all of that. But when you look at

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:55.800
[Amit Varma]: journalism today, has that also changed over the years that you're also looking at the craft and

00:29:55.800 --> 00:30:02.360
[Amit Varma]: practice of journalism with that critical eye of someone who does it herself? And also as a sort of

00:30:02.360 --> 00:30:11.640
[Amit Varma]: an adjunct question to that, does your sort of understanding of data, then sort of also affect

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:17.800
[Amit Varma]: how you look at the work of others? And does it then seem that much more inadequate and misinformed?

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:22.760
[Guest]: Right. So one of the most frustrating things to me that continues, see, the thing is, I'm very

00:30:22.760 --> 00:30:29.880
[Guest]: much a mainstream media person. And even though I'm not in newsroom now, I sort of think and

00:30:29.880 --> 00:30:37.080
[Guest]: even plan or imagine very much around the newsroom. So it's incredibly frustrating to me

00:30:37.080 --> 00:30:42.760
[Guest]: to see that although newsroom integration is something that has existed on a Microsoft,

00:30:42.760 --> 00:30:47.960
[Guest]: on a PPT slides for the last 10 years in every presentation made to anyone in the media,

00:30:47.960 --> 00:30:53.720
[Guest]: it's not happening in any meaningful way. And I see this particularly for data stuff. So,

00:30:53.720 --> 00:31:00.040
[Guest]: you know, a couple of things have changed in how I consume the news. One is time, one is

00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:06.360
[Guest]: reading much more on my phone and, you know, than reading physical newspapers. And in the sort of

00:31:06.360 --> 00:31:11.160
[Guest]: stuff that I want to read considering, as you're saying, considering what I want to write as well.

00:31:11.160 --> 00:31:18.360
[Guest]: I always find it very amusing when journalists sort of express fears about bots, because so much

00:31:18.360 --> 00:31:24.840
[Guest]: of the time journalists are actually writing like bots. So one of the things about COVID coverage

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:30.760
[Guest]: that I've noticed is that I regularly open something that I feel was written by a bot,

00:31:30.760 --> 00:31:36.360
[Guest]: because it will say so many cases today and this region more and that region less. And

00:31:36.360 --> 00:31:44.840
[Guest]: it's painful to think that it wasn't written by a bot. This shouldn't be what, and this is not one

00:31:44.840 --> 00:31:50.920
[Guest]: news article, right? If you put the same search words in Google News, you'll find about 50 Indian

00:31:50.920 --> 00:31:57.000
[Guest]: publications alone will have written exactly the same thing. So I'm very much a fan of lots of

00:31:57.880 --> 00:32:05.960
[Guest]: little regular news. I enjoy my T.O.I. kind of bits of everything in the city news, I think.

00:32:06.920 --> 00:32:12.200
[Guest]: I think it works very well for a city newspaper. I don't think that that's a bad way of going about

00:32:12.200 --> 00:32:19.080
[Guest]: it. But if you look at it as a consumer, not as a captive consumer of one newspaper,

00:32:19.080 --> 00:32:27.240
[Guest]: it's incredible how little value add most news articles are doing and what a waste of time it is

00:32:27.240 --> 00:32:33.400
[Guest]: for the journalists who are working really hard to put that out. Yes, the working on data has

00:32:33.400 --> 00:32:40.280
[Guest]: made it impossible for me now to see a good news report that lacks that. So for example,

00:32:40.280 --> 00:32:46.360
[Guest]: it's ruined political reporting for me because I just cannot wrap my head around the I landed

00:32:46.360 --> 00:32:51.160
[Guest]: in this constituency, one JAT is saying this, one Abhikash Mann is saying this, one SCN. I

00:32:51.160 --> 00:32:57.720
[Guest]: cannot wrap my head around that kind of journalism anymore because I don't know what to do with it.

00:32:57.720 --> 00:33:03.800
[Guest]: And most large Indian states are pretty well covered by opinion polling. Now there's differences

00:33:03.800 --> 00:33:09.080
[Guest]: in the quality of the polling. But to read one of these, you know, parachuted, even if not

00:33:09.080 --> 00:33:14.840
[Guest]: parachuted, even by people who deeply understand the region, I just find it impossible to read it

00:33:14.840 --> 00:33:19.800
[Guest]: anymore. It shouldn't. These are, you know, hardworking journalists who are going out there

00:33:19.800 --> 00:33:23.960
[Guest]: and as such getting you the voices from the ground. But I don't know what to do with it

00:33:23.960 --> 00:33:30.120
[Guest]: anymore. I don't know what part of my brain that's thinking about an election to put it into

00:33:30.120 --> 00:33:37.240
[Guest]: anymore. It's like watching a fun show now. It's not something that I can slot into any usable

00:33:37.240 --> 00:33:42.280
[Guest]: thing. And I think a lot of political reporters feel the other way. They feel very frustrated by

00:33:43.240 --> 00:33:48.040
[Guest]: opinion polling, heavy reporting, which they feel is like missing all the nuances on the ground.

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:53.720
[Guest]: But and opinion polls get it so wrong too, right? So they do feel that how can you hold this as

00:33:53.720 --> 00:33:57.240
[Guest]: some sort of gospel when they're getting it wrong? We get the real feel on the ground. But yeah,

00:33:57.240 --> 00:34:04.280
[Guest]: that's what it's done for me. And another thing is when there are elements that can be answered

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:11.640
[Guest]: through numbers, when it doesn't happen, then it leaves me very deeply dissatisfied. So more than

00:34:11.640 --> 00:34:16.120
[Guest]: even looking at the craft of writing differently, what I've been doing a bit in the last few months

00:34:16.120 --> 00:34:20.680
[Guest]: is looking at podcasts differently. I always listen to them a bit, but I think I listen to

00:34:20.680 --> 00:34:25.960
[Guest]: journalism podcasts a little more now. In general, I feel like I hear too much from journalists,

00:34:25.960 --> 00:34:30.760
[Guest]: and I try not to listen to more of them, especially American journalists. But there

00:34:30.760 --> 00:34:36.040
[Guest]: were a couple of podcasts that I wanted to listen to. And one that I was listening to over the last

00:34:36.040 --> 00:34:41.160
[Guest]: few days was called Canary by the Washington Post. And it's by the journalist Amy Britton.

00:34:41.160 --> 00:34:48.440
[Guest]: The entire podcast covers her investigation into, well, it starts into a sexual assault trial.

00:34:48.440 --> 00:34:53.000
[Guest]: Now, this is something I feel very strongly about. Not strongly, it's something I sort of

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:58.280
[Guest]: engage deeply in, and I'm not sure yet what to feel about the reporting of sexual assault.

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:05.000
[Guest]: You know, it's beyond any, nobody still needs to discuss the fact that the way women complainants

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:09.880
[Guest]: are written about is a problem, that trials through the judicial system, the questions that

00:35:09.880 --> 00:35:14.200
[Guest]: are still allowed, the way the police behaves, all of that is a problem. But I still have a

00:35:14.200 --> 00:35:20.680
[Guest]: problem with over-involved journalism around sexual assault, starting from the point of using

00:35:20.680 --> 00:35:25.240
[Guest]: things like victim and perpetrator instead of complainant and accused, all of that stuff.

00:35:25.240 --> 00:35:33.720
[Guest]: So, this podcast centers, starts around a sexual assault trial in which the man admits to the

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:40.040
[Guest]: crime, but it seems as if the judge has given him a lower sentence. And then what we end up

00:35:40.040 --> 00:35:45.160
[Guest]: finding out is that after she writes about, Amy Britton writes about this trial, because the

00:35:45.160 --> 00:35:49.720
[Guest]: complainant didn't take it lying down, and she started, you know, pasting flyers around the city

00:35:49.720 --> 00:35:54.600
[Guest]: saying that this person has been convicted, he's admitted to it, he did, you know, he was a serial

00:35:54.600 --> 00:35:59.800
[Guest]: offender, but see, it hasn't, you know, he was back at his job, in fact, he'd got a promotion,

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:04.600
[Guest]: stuff like that. It was all factual, what she was putting out. And after she wrote, Amy Britton

00:36:04.600 --> 00:36:10.440
[Guest]: wrote about it, she was contacted by a woman who ended up telling her the story of how she was

00:36:10.440 --> 00:36:18.280
[Guest]: herself systematically sexually harassed and molested by the judge in the case, you know,

00:36:18.280 --> 00:36:24.840
[Guest]: many years before. So, that part is really a model of journalism. It's, you know, corroboration,

00:36:24.840 --> 00:36:30.520
[Guest]: contemporaneous accounts, letters, all of that, none of which you see in, you know, sexual assault.

00:36:31.240 --> 00:36:35.640
[Guest]: This isn't sexual assault, this is a complaint of a sexual assault, right, not a trial. You never

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:41.160
[Guest]: see that in the coverage here, and it's great to see that. But I can see her sort of moving this

00:36:41.160 --> 00:36:49.240
[Guest]: two words. So, did this, his own experience affect his sentencing and the way he was as a judge

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:55.720
[Guest]: because of what he had done in his own life? And what happens, she puts her data journalist onto

00:36:55.720 --> 00:37:00.360
[Guest]: it, the Washington Post data journalist, and ultimately, they come up short because they just

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:08.120
[Guest]: can't sort out the court data. And part of me was feeling, well, you know, open 100 tabs and read

00:37:08.120 --> 00:37:13.000
[Guest]: them one by one, but also there was some information they just could not get. So, she doesn't answer

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:19.320
[Guest]: that part. So, she says, I don't have an answer on that. And to me, that felt, I felt like I was

00:37:19.320 --> 00:37:24.600
[Guest]: being led down a path and then just completely, you know, disappointed on that, because I did

00:37:24.600 --> 00:37:32.760
[Guest]: want that data part in that story. Otherwise, this was a very well told story about how one judge

00:37:32.760 --> 00:37:38.280
[Guest]: 30 years ago had sexually harassed and molested someone. And that's, that's not the story that I

00:37:38.280 --> 00:37:46.840
[Guest]: felt I was being sold at all. So, yeah, it really does take away from my enjoyment of a lot of

00:37:47.400 --> 00:37:51.960
[Guest]: reporting now. And of course, when in cases where I can see that the data exists and should have

00:37:51.960 --> 00:37:56.600
[Guest]: been used, and maybe in some cases would have even not answered exactly that, as I said,

00:37:56.600 --> 00:38:01.080
[Guest]: particularly for political reporting, it's absolutely ruined election coverage for me now.

00:38:01.080 --> 00:38:05.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'm struck by a couple of the things you said. One, of course, I like your, I mean,

00:38:05.880 --> 00:38:09.880
[Amit Varma]: it made me almost LOL, when you said that so many people write like bots, and you can't make

00:38:09.880 --> 00:38:14.440
[Amit Varma]: out the difference. Because I think, you know, we as journalists and writers, we can fall into such

00:38:14.440 --> 00:38:19.560
[Amit Varma]: reflexive habits of both thinking and writing, that for all practical purposes, we might as well

00:38:19.560 --> 00:38:23.560
[Amit Varma]: be bots, except that we are incompetent bots, because we don't have that kind of computing

00:38:23.560 --> 00:38:27.640
[Amit Varma]: power. Like I often say that Trump would fail the Turing test. And I think that might well be

00:38:27.640 --> 00:38:31.720
[Amit Varma]: true of many other humans as well. The second part that you said that really struck me and I'm

00:38:31.720 --> 00:38:37.000
[Amit Varma]: obviously going to search out canary and binge on it now is a bit where journalist at the end says

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:41.640
[Amit Varma]: that I don't really have an answer, which is so refreshing, because there are, you know, it's in

00:38:41.640 --> 00:38:46.280
[Amit Varma]: India, for example, it's almost like you have a compulsion to give an answer. And this percolates

00:38:46.280 --> 00:38:50.280
[Amit Varma]: down for some strange reason to everyday life where if you ask anyone on the street, the

00:38:50.280 --> 00:38:54.120
[Amit Varma]: directions to somewhere, even if they don't know, they will feel compelled to tell you that

00:38:54.120 --> 00:38:59.800
[Amit Varma]: wahan jaiye, wahan se daine, wahan se baine, and so on and so forth. My other sort of question,

00:38:59.800 --> 00:39:03.880
[Amit Varma]: which came out of what you were saying earlier was, you know, when you were talking about how

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:08.760
[Amit Varma]: moving to the south, you realize that there are areas which are, for example, not covered by Delhi

00:39:08.760 --> 00:39:13.000
[Amit Varma]: questions that they are not asking, and so on. And I was being interviewed for another podcast

00:39:13.720 --> 00:39:17.480
[Amit Varma]: today where I was chatting about TikTok, where, you know, I taught a brief course on TikTok in

00:39:17.480 --> 00:39:22.760
[Amit Varma]: Indian society. And I'm quite, you know, I love TikTok. And one of the things that to me TikTok

00:39:22.760 --> 00:39:29.080
[Amit Varma]: did was that before it came along, popular culture had arbiters in the sense that, you know, you had

00:39:29.080 --> 00:39:34.520
[Amit Varma]: Bollywood and it is as one example, you have other film industries also. But for example, you have

00:39:34.520 --> 00:39:38.680
[Amit Varma]: Bollywood, they're based in Bombay, there are elites who run them, some of them are, you know,

00:39:38.680 --> 00:39:42.760
[Amit Varma]: these old school elites who have these regressive attitudes from the past been in Bombay all their

00:39:42.760 --> 00:39:48.280
[Amit Varma]: lives. Others have, you know, are all your foreign educated young elites who've come in with their

00:39:48.280 --> 00:39:52.840
[Amit Varma]: attitudes, and they don't get the real India at all. And what TikTok kind of did was that it

00:39:52.840 --> 00:39:57.240
[Amit Varma]: empowered millions of people, not just in terms of letting them express themselves, but of giving

00:39:57.240 --> 00:40:01.960
[Amit Varma]: them a platform where other people like them were expressing themselves. And suddenly that became

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:06.920
[Amit Varma]: the popular culture, you know, bottoms up kind of way. And it was not just, you know, what these

00:40:06.920 --> 00:40:11.560
[Amit Varma]: arbiters kind of put out. And it struck me while you were speaking, and I know this is a bit of a

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:15.720
[Amit Varma]: tangent, but it struck me while you were speaking that, you know, is there a case to be made that

00:40:15.720 --> 00:40:21.560
[Amit Varma]: that is what the situation is in Indian journalism as well, that you have these arbiters, you have

00:40:21.560 --> 00:40:27.720
[Amit Varma]: these, you know, big media houses, even where you have independent outfits that do such amazing work

00:40:27.720 --> 00:40:32.120
[Amit Varma]: like Stolen Wire, and so on. They are still run by conventional journalists who have the

00:40:32.120 --> 00:40:37.480
[Amit Varma]: conventional points of view, you know, and maybe they're all really missing things, not out of any

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:43.320
[Amit Varma]: blindness or incapacity, but it's just the way that it is. And, you know, that there are gaps

00:40:43.320 --> 00:40:49.080
[Guest]: there that could be filled. Yeah, I do think that we have not allowed ourselves to go crazy a little

00:40:49.080 --> 00:40:57.400
[Guest]: bit trying to think both about form and content. So I do, you know, even when I was writing

00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:03.560
[Guest]: data stories, and that's sometimes still feedback I might still get, which is that,

00:41:05.080 --> 00:41:10.200
[Guest]: why don't you humanize it a little, and then the sort of temptation to have the first paragraph

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:17.240
[Guest]: being a sort of archetype of the type of person that the data story describes. And then in paragraph

00:41:17.240 --> 00:41:22.440
[Guest]: two, you come to the data element that sort of contextualizes. I see that in a fair amount of

00:41:22.440 --> 00:41:27.720
[Guest]: data journalism. And I feel like what that does is allow the reporter to, if it is a choice to

00:41:27.720 --> 00:41:34.440
[Guest]: tick the box that I spoke to real people, this wasn't just Amche journalism, I included human

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:40.200
[Guest]: aspects in it. I brought in an element of creativity into what's otherwise quite cool.

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:47.720
[Guest]: So yeah, you know, it's so hard to think of a piece of journalism that truly surprises you,

00:41:47.720 --> 00:41:53.800
[Guest]: right. And it doesn't have to be that way. And I agree with you that I don't understand why

00:41:55.000 --> 00:42:00.520
[Guest]: newer places have not allowed themselves to experiment with that, to the point that they

00:42:00.520 --> 00:42:06.200
[Guest]: really read like the Indian Express if they're one sort of journalism. So there was and I was

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:10.680
[Guest]: looking trying to look this up before this call, but I didn't get to the name in time,

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:16.440
[Guest]: you might remember this. At the beginning of the pandemic, there was a guy who wrote a piece for

00:42:16.440 --> 00:42:20.600
[Guest]: the Atlantic, I want to say, which sort of described what happens to your body when the

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:27.240
[Guest]: virus hits you. But through a hypothetical story of a man who's, you know, meets a friend for lunch

00:42:27.240 --> 00:42:33.160
[Guest]: without realizing it. But the science in it was hardcore, it, you know, got right into all of the

00:42:33.160 --> 00:42:39.240
[Guest]: cells and all of that. So I felt like I did actually learn about how the virus does the

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:43.880
[Guest]: human body and what it does. That was the first time I sort of properly understood what the

00:42:43.880 --> 00:42:51.480
[Guest]: cytokine storm even means. Though it was told in a sort of semi fictionalized way. And, you know,

00:42:51.480 --> 00:42:57.720
[Guest]: I just remember that just struck me also right now, because these kinds of stories that truly

00:42:57.720 --> 00:43:04.200
[Guest]: surprise you, I feel like I can really count them because there are so few when the form really

00:43:04.200 --> 00:43:13.960
[Guest]: takes you by surprise. I think people are doing much more inventive stuff in video. So that's

00:43:13.960 --> 00:43:20.120
[Guest]: where you occasionally see people breaking out of that very old school NDTV documentary kind of

00:43:20.120 --> 00:43:27.640
[Guest]: format of reporting, reporting on everything. And the other thing that struck me when you were

00:43:27.640 --> 00:43:33.640
[Guest]: giving a TikTok example, and when I was thinking about the South is that, to me in a way, Tamil,

00:43:33.640 --> 00:43:39.560
[Guest]: which I am in no way fluent in, and I knew no Tamil until I moved to Chennai, and I'm still

00:43:39.560 --> 00:43:45.080
[Guest]: not great at it. It was like that. It was like, you know, what maybe learning about TikTok felt

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:52.360
[Guest]: like to you seeing this entire universe of people who other filters and bubbles had not brought to

00:43:52.360 --> 00:43:58.280
[Guest]: you maybe or to any TikTok user. Tamil feels like that to me. And I've got nowhere near, you know,

00:43:58.280 --> 00:44:03.560
[Guest]: even reading. So it's not literature. It's just popular culture that I am in some ways able to

00:44:03.560 --> 00:44:09.480
[Guest]: consume right now. Everyone likes to say this about their own language, but I truly so far feel

00:44:09.480 --> 00:44:19.240
[Guest]: that the Tamil meme industry is just off the hook. They are so funny, so quick, so savage.

00:44:19.240 --> 00:44:24.200
[Guest]: And these are some of the great, you know, untranslatable, because again, when I see

00:44:24.200 --> 00:44:28.600
[Guest]: the Tamil pop culture that filters up and makes it to the rest of the country,

00:44:28.600 --> 00:44:35.320
[Guest]: it's the most boring, sanitized, sort of yuppie stuff that gets popular. The guys who are on the,

00:44:35.320 --> 00:44:41.160
[Guest]: you know, comedy circuits, but the stuff that's actually getting shared over WhatsApp or that's

00:44:41.160 --> 00:44:47.320
[Guest]: really, you know, popular among friends or my husband and his friends over here is so much

00:44:47.320 --> 00:44:53.800
[Guest]: more subversive. So it's rare. Well, something like TikTok would be something that opens these

00:44:53.800 --> 00:44:59.800
[Guest]: worlds to you later in life, right? I think I have no brain cells left for any more new social

00:44:59.800 --> 00:45:05.480
[Guest]: media. So I've given up on that now. But I hope that Tamil can be that for me a little bit, you

00:45:05.480 --> 00:45:13.000
[Guest]: know, this opening up of people of a culture that arbiters had not, my own arbiters had not allowed

00:45:13.720 --> 00:45:17.320
[Amit Varma]: to get to me so far. That's fascinating. I was just trying to look for the, you know,

00:45:17.320 --> 00:45:20.200
[Amit Varma]: the story in the Atlantic, which you were mentioning, we'll take a quick commercial

