[Amit Varma]: days to find it. We're recording this on Monday, October 19. It comes out this Sunday. So without

00:47:24.280 --> 00:47:29.400
[Amit Varma]: finding it, it's going to come tonight. Yeah, yeah, eventually. And even though I haven't read

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:35.480
[Amit Varma]: the story, I suspect I can't sleep. One has discovered it. Let's get back to you know,

00:47:35.480 --> 00:47:40.360
[Amit Varma]: your fascinating journey, discovering data. I mean, I mean, one thing that often strikes me is

00:47:40.360 --> 00:47:46.520
[Amit Varma]: that I just find that term itself data journalism kind of odd because it's almost like saying,

00:47:46.520 --> 00:47:51.000
[Amit Varma]: oh, that person is a word journalist or that person's the part of journalism he does is

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:56.120
[Amit Varma]: writing or reporting or whatever. And to me, all of those are kind of a package which come together.

00:47:56.120 --> 00:48:01.560
[Amit Varma]: If you are a reporter or a journalist, you are supposed to examine the facts. And data after all

00:48:01.560 --> 00:48:06.760
[Amit Varma]: is a collection of facts. So you know, is there a point at which the data journalist becomes a

00:48:07.480 --> 00:48:13.880
[Amit Varma]: different sort of beast? Like, when did you start thinking of data is something special that kind of

00:48:13.880 --> 00:48:19.400
[Amit Varma]: data consideration of data sets you apart from, you know, not from others, maybe, but maybe from

00:48:19.400 --> 00:48:24.040
[Amit Varma]: the person you were previously? Like, what was the first TIL moment that you got from data?

00:48:24.680 --> 00:48:30.920
[Guest]: So I think what happens and what sets things apart then and then what does create a unique

00:48:30.920 --> 00:48:39.640
[Guest]: category is when you are able to independently come up with insights from numbers by yourself.

00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:45.960
[Guest]: And this is important for a number of reasons for, you know, across journalism, the point is to be

00:48:45.960 --> 00:48:52.920
[Guest]: able to move past the handout, the press release and be able to say something so that that means

00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:58.840
[Guest]: that you develop a mastery of some sort, either you're able to, you know, understand what was

00:48:58.840 --> 00:49:04.040
[Guest]: missed, you get to the spot and find what really happened, or you're able to get to multiple sources

00:49:04.040 --> 00:49:09.720
[Guest]: who tell you what really happened, or you're able to look at numbers and say something entirely new,

00:49:10.520 --> 00:49:16.120
[Guest]: that hasn't been told to you, and that hasn't been put out like that. So I think that came much

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:22.520
[Guest]: later, there was months and months, maybe even years, but months and months, definitely faithfully

00:49:22.520 --> 00:49:29.080
[Guest]: reporting what the NSSO report was wanted to say, before getting to the point, you know, starting

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:34.200
[Guest]: from the point where I was able to say new things, to moving to the point where I was able to say

00:49:34.200 --> 00:49:41.480
[Guest]: things that the press handout was very purposively not saying. So I think, you know, one of the

00:49:42.040 --> 00:49:49.560
[Guest]: moments that it really struck home was, I want to say in 2015, the highly delayed

00:49:49.560 --> 00:49:56.920
[Guest]: census religion data was finally put out by the new government. It was late, it had been expected

00:49:56.920 --> 00:50:03.880
[Guest]: before the elections, but I suspect the UPA government just, you know, just out of like sort

00:50:03.880 --> 00:50:08.680
[Guest]: of lily-livered nervousness sat on it, for no particular reason, maybe they just felt that this

00:50:08.680 --> 00:50:15.000
[Guest]: was a conversation they did not want coming up at all, because of the sort of criticism that came

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:22.440
[Guest]: their way anyway. So the census organization in India comes under the Home Ministry, and for a lot

00:50:22.440 --> 00:50:28.600
[Guest]: of important census releases, the Home Minister, Rajnath Singh at the time, or any Home Minister

00:50:28.600 --> 00:50:33.080
[Guest]: in the past as well, would have a press conference, and the Census Commissioner would be there,

00:50:33.080 --> 00:50:38.760
[Guest]: the Home Minister would be there, they would put it all out. The census data operation is truly,

00:50:38.760 --> 00:50:46.280
[Guest]: uniquely opaque in a lot of ways. So a lot of the archival census data that I have is on CDs,

00:50:46.280 --> 00:50:53.240
[Guest]: which I got from the census, when I used to report in Delhi, it's not available on their

00:50:54.120 --> 00:51:01.320
[Guest]: website, and it's not easily available even in a book form. So what happened is that at 7pm

00:51:01.320 --> 00:51:06.680
[Guest]: on a weeknight, the person who covered Home Ministry told me that they put out a press

00:51:06.680 --> 00:51:13.960
[Guest]: release, and the press release says that now the proportion of Hindus, Muslims, Sikhs, etc. in

00:51:13.960 --> 00:51:17.960
[Guest]: India is this much, this much, this much. Hindus have grown at this rate, Muslims have grown at

00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:25.080
[Guest]: that rate. And clearly, the growth rate of the population of Muslims was much higher than that

00:51:25.080 --> 00:51:30.840
[Guest]: of Hindus. And that stood out in the second paragraph of the numbers, there was no context,

00:51:30.840 --> 00:51:36.760
[Guest]: no background, no past numbers, nothing given. And that's it, that was 7 o'clock, and obviously

00:51:36.760 --> 00:51:43.400
[Guest]: everybody had to run with the story. So I think what happened that day is, A, because I had been

00:51:43.960 --> 00:51:50.040
[Guest]: by then at The Hindu for a couple of years as a journalist whose job was to look at numbers and

00:51:50.040 --> 00:51:56.280
[Guest]: data specifically, it was part of my job, you know, I took it very seriously as part of my job

00:51:56.280 --> 00:52:03.240
[Guest]: to create these archives of data for myself. So I had extensive past data, even though it wasn't

00:52:03.240 --> 00:52:09.320
[Guest]: available from the census's website by then. And to create, as for all journalism, a phone book of

00:52:09.320 --> 00:52:15.480
[Guest]: people who I could call upon to interpret data at any hour. So what we were able to do is that

00:52:16.040 --> 00:52:23.480
[Guest]: we were able to look at the proportion of people by religious group from pre-independence time

00:52:23.480 --> 00:52:29.320
[Guest]: onwards. And what that showed and what was confirmed by the demographers I spoke to was that

00:52:30.120 --> 00:52:36.760
[Guest]: the Muslim population growth rate was expected to slow as Muslim women got better educated and

00:52:36.760 --> 00:52:43.080
[Guest]: with better access to health and as Muslim incomes rose. What had happened actually between 2001 and

00:52:43.080 --> 00:52:51.800
[Guest]: 11 is that the Muslim growth rate had slowed quicker than the Hindu growth rate even, and

00:52:51.800 --> 00:52:56.920
[Guest]: quicker than expected. None of this meant that, you know, the Muslim population was

00:52:56.920 --> 00:53:04.600
[Guest]: had shrunk or any of the, it was a nuanced sort of change. But to me, the reason that this was

00:53:04.600 --> 00:53:11.320
[Guest]: the news was not just out of some sort of, you know, liberal belief. It's also that the fact

00:53:11.320 --> 00:53:17.560
[Guest]: that Muslims are growing faster than Hindus has been unchanged since like 1930. So I didn't

00:53:17.560 --> 00:53:23.000
[Guest]: understand how that could be a news point in 2015. If there's a change in the speed of growth,

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:28.200
[Guest]: that's what demographic transitions are all about. And that's what the story needed to be.

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:35.800
[Guest]: So every single newspaper the next day reported that Hindus now below 80%. I mean, as of 80% is

00:53:35.800 --> 00:53:41.080
[Guest]: some scientific number. It was quite immaterial, but I, you know, that was the easy number to pick

00:53:41.080 --> 00:53:46.040
[Guest]: up from the first few lines of the press release. And our very Hindu headline at the time said,

00:53:46.040 --> 00:53:52.280
[Guest]: you know, Muslim population growth slows. And it sounded like literally the opposite of what

00:53:52.280 --> 00:53:58.360
[Guest]: everybody else was saying. It created a big issue on social media. I was actually, you know,

00:53:58.360 --> 00:54:04.760
[Guest]: stopped and even the Hindus always and asked by people in HR and finance, why is our paper saying

00:54:04.760 --> 00:54:10.920
[Guest]: the opposite of what even the Tamil newspapers that they were reading or any of the other

00:54:10.920 --> 00:54:15.160
[Guest]: more southern focused newspapers that they were reading were saying? I think that was one of the

00:54:15.160 --> 00:54:22.120
[Guest]: moments that I felt that there was value in this as a specialization and it not being left to the

00:54:22.120 --> 00:54:27.960
[Guest]: poor, overburdened and under equipped home ministry reporter to have to come up with the

00:54:27.960 --> 00:54:35.320
[Guest]: best possible news report around it that she could at 7pm and then be criticized the next day

00:54:35.320 --> 00:54:41.080
[Guest]: for feeding into propaganda or a narrative when she had just not been given the tools that she

00:54:41.080 --> 00:54:48.200
[Guest]: would need to be able to say something more. So I'm not sure I answered your question.

00:54:48.200 --> 00:54:54.360
[Amit Varma]: No, you did. You did. I mean, it's such a fantastic example of using data to go past

00:54:54.360 --> 00:54:58.680
[Amit Varma]: the intuitive conclusion that one might draw and go a little deeper and find that, hey,

00:54:58.680 --> 00:55:03.240
[Amit Varma]: the truth is exactly the opposite. And obviously, your Hindu headline wasn't in any way contradictory

00:55:03.240 --> 00:55:08.360
[Amit Varma]: of what the others are saying. It's just that is going deeper and kind of giving more perspective.

00:55:08.360 --> 00:55:13.160
[Amit Varma]: A couple of questions kind of arise from this, like as this very example shows, in fact,

00:55:13.160 --> 00:55:18.680
[Amit Varma]: that you can always present the data or interpret the data to fit your own biases.

00:55:18.680 --> 00:55:23.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, we live in times where it seems that narratives are more important than facts or

00:55:23.240 --> 00:55:29.080
[Amit Varma]: than truth, you know, where possibly enabled by social media and the way WhatsApp and all

00:55:29.080 --> 00:55:33.800
[Amit Varma]: has been weaponized. People choose narratives to choose whatever facts fit those narratives.

00:55:33.800 --> 00:55:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's basically it. And, you know, whatever ways data is presented in goes through that

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:44.920
[Amit Varma]: narrative and they ignore everything else. So a couple of questions here. One is that

00:55:44.920 --> 00:55:50.600
[Amit Varma]: even at a personal level, every time you choose a story to do, and in the case of a data journalist,

00:55:50.600 --> 00:55:55.560
[Amit Varma]: every time you choose what analysis to run on a particular piece of data or what further

00:55:55.560 --> 00:56:00.920
[Amit Varma]: inquiries to make, your own biases do come into play because we're all biased as individuals.

00:56:00.920 --> 00:56:05.800
[Amit Varma]: And good journalists obviously are aware of those biases and they just try to do the most

00:56:05.800 --> 00:56:11.560
[Amit Varma]: fair job that they can in terms of negotiating with facts. So part one, I'll come to part two

00:56:11.560 --> 00:56:16.920
[Amit Varma]: later. But part one of my question would be that then do you is that something that you've had to

00:56:16.920 --> 00:56:21.160
[Amit Varma]: watch out for where you sometimes have to take a step back from yourself and say that, OK,

00:56:21.160 --> 00:56:27.080
[Amit Varma]: this might be the way I am approaching it. But let me just, you know, take a step out of that.

00:56:27.080 --> 00:56:32.040
[Amit Varma]: Or do you feel that completely taking a step out of that is kind of impossible? This this is

00:56:32.040 --> 00:56:37.480
[Guest]: something I spend so much time thinking about. And when I was listening to Samant on your podcast

00:56:38.360 --> 00:56:44.680
[Guest]: and, you know, you were talking about subjectivity and bias. And I think someone said that,

00:56:45.800 --> 00:56:50.840
[Guest]: you know, what's important is being fair, going in with fairness and, you know, subjectivity,

00:56:50.840 --> 00:56:57.720
[Guest]: bias, all of these are things that exist in all humans. And I sort of kept that, you know,

00:56:57.720 --> 00:57:03.320
[Guest]: part of my head to when I try to answer these questions for myself as well, that what am I

00:57:03.320 --> 00:57:10.040
[Guest]: aiming for? What what do I think I'm going in with? What am I as a human able to do and what

00:57:10.040 --> 00:57:15.800
[Guest]: should I aspire to? So I would agree that fairness is one of the things that I aspire to.

00:57:15.800 --> 00:57:22.360
[Guest]: There is no doubt that particularly now that I'm in a position to choose the stories I do

00:57:22.360 --> 00:57:29.400
[Guest]: much more than and I'm assigned stories much less. There is absolutely a few things that I

00:57:29.400 --> 00:57:36.920
[Guest]: go into the data looking for and specifically report on. So I go into most data sets looking

00:57:36.920 --> 00:57:43.080
[Guest]: for gender and caste dimensions because these are things of interest to me and what I'm most keen

00:57:43.080 --> 00:57:51.720
[Guest]: on reporting on. Again, this sort of harks back to the quaint UPA era. It's hard to believe then,

00:57:51.720 --> 00:57:58.600
[Guest]: but one of the biggest cleavages then was between the centre left and the left of the left. It's so

00:57:58.600 --> 00:58:03.880
[Guest]: hard to imagine that that was the key cleavage then. But I remember, you know, I don't want to

00:58:03.880 --> 00:58:08.280
[Guest]: date it too specifically because I don't want to talk about who this was, but someone who

00:58:08.280 --> 00:58:13.400
[Guest]: assigned, you used to assign me stories at one point when I was reporting on the census.

00:58:14.680 --> 00:58:21.080
[Guest]: And you know, this was information on asset ownership by household. And he very clearly

00:58:21.080 --> 00:58:25.320
[Guest]: told me, I said, you know, I was, it was very early, so I was just not sure what part to look

00:58:25.320 --> 00:58:30.840
[Guest]: at. And he said, see, don't tell me the things that have got better. And that was one of the

00:58:30.840 --> 00:58:38.040
[Guest]: defining features of how we all, of how the UPA was covered, which is that these, you know,

00:58:38.040 --> 00:58:45.400
[Guest]: neoliberal, like following market forces sort of things, turning their backs on the PDS. And,

00:58:45.400 --> 00:58:51.320
[Guest]: you know, everybody's trying to say liberalisation has been great. But look, after 10 years of UPA,

00:58:51.320 --> 00:58:55.880
[Guest]: people are so poor still. And, you know, asset ownership, only so many people have a cell phone

00:58:55.880 --> 00:59:02.520
[Guest]: and have a toilet and that. And, you know, of course, one of the things to, for everybody to

00:59:02.520 --> 00:59:10.200
[Guest]: think about is the enormous damage that this sort of discussion created even to the overall

00:59:10.200 --> 00:59:15.880
[Guest]: political space, to the, to possibly even to electoral outcomes. I mean, that's obviously

00:59:15.880 --> 00:59:21.880
[Guest]: not what that election was fought or won on. But it's really something to think about how

00:59:21.880 --> 00:59:28.040
[Guest]: dangerous and damaging that was, particularly because it was not in any way borne out by the

00:59:28.040 --> 00:59:35.400
[Guest]: data. 2005 to 2015 was the period of the fastest reduction in poverty in Indian history. And

00:59:36.280 --> 00:59:41.800
[Guest]: it's, some of it we didn't know then, but some of it should have been obvious and was absolutely

00:59:41.800 --> 00:59:49.160
[Guest]: not the story of that election. So, you know, we were talking earlier as well about what I studied

00:59:49.160 --> 00:59:56.200
[Guest]: or what I studied and then the questions that I had to ask myself. Having studied and sort of

00:59:56.200 --> 01:00:04.440
[Guest]: come up in a, you know, vaguely leftish atmosphere, one of the things that I did have to sort of

01:00:04.440 --> 01:00:11.720
[Guest]: think hard and confront and worry about whether I was trying to sort of torture the data into

01:00:11.720 --> 01:00:19.080
[Guest]: constantly confessing that some of these leftist truths hold true, which is that liberalisation was

01:00:19.080 --> 01:00:26.440
[Guest]: bad, which is that, you know, migration is happening at a mass and dangerously terrifying scale,

01:00:26.440 --> 01:00:31.720
[Guest]: showing mass impoverishment of the poorest of the poor from the villages, all of these things that

01:00:31.720 --> 01:00:38.200
[Guest]: are not borne out by the data. That was a particularly damaging time for that sort of

01:00:38.200 --> 01:00:43.000
[Guest]: journalism. There's other kind of falsehoods that are happening now. And we, you know, we all know

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:49.560
[Guest]: about them and focus on them and criticise them. But it's important to think of how damaging these,

01:00:50.280 --> 01:00:55.160
[Guest]: this sort of now what looks like a micro-polarisation, but that was a polarisation

01:00:55.160 --> 01:01:01.800
[Guest]: that existed in an ideological divide that existed then. The shoddy and sometimes downright

01:01:01.800 --> 01:01:08.280
[Guest]: dishonest journalism that happened around that then is also pretty shameful.

01:01:08.280 --> 01:01:13.160
[Amit Varma]: And it's pretty telling to me, like you pointed out, when you sort of found that sort of nuance

01:01:13.720 --> 01:01:17.240
[Amit Varma]: in that headline that you ran in the Hindu, and you said that you were actually accosted in the

01:01:17.240 --> 01:01:22.120
[Amit Varma]: corridor by people wanting to know and all of that, that also tells you a little bit about

01:01:22.120 --> 01:01:26.760
[Amit Varma]: the desire to believe certain narratives and the pressure to conform to them and all of that.

01:01:26.760 --> 01:01:32.440
[Amit Varma]: And my sort of follow up question from there is that, you know, does, I mean, it's a two part

01:01:32.440 --> 01:01:37.720
[Amit Varma]: question, part one, and I don't want to be too cynical about it. But does journalism of this

01:01:37.720 --> 01:01:42.520
[Amit Varma]: sort, rigorous database journalism that is going that one or two steps deeper,

01:01:42.520 --> 01:01:47.400
[Amit Varma]: does it really make a difference? Is there an appetite and a longing for it? And part two of

01:01:47.400 --> 01:01:54.600
[Amit Varma]: that would be that, assuming that the answer is no, or that it is not enough to, you know, validate

01:01:54.600 --> 01:02:01.000
[Amit Varma]: what we do on a daily basis, is it still almost a moral imperative for us to continue doing this

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:06.680
[Amit Varma]: kind of work so that there is a record for the future, like in a sense, like you've pointed out

01:02:06.680 --> 01:02:10.520
[Amit Varma]: earlier that, you know, in a sense, you're probably one of the pioneers of data journalism in India,

01:02:10.520 --> 01:02:14.280
[Amit Varma]: right? So you had to do all the manual work of going through hundreds of court judgments and all

01:02:14.280 --> 01:02:19.960
[Amit Varma]: that. But now everybody who works in data, who works in data journalism, is, in a sense, creating

01:02:19.960 --> 01:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: a repository for their future selves, and future data journalists. So is that something that you

01:02:26.920 --> 01:02:32.760
[Amit Varma]: take seriously? And are you more hopeful about, you know, your journalism, having an impact in

01:02:32.760 --> 01:02:37.640
[Amit Varma]: these current times? And you know, I seem to be from my question. Yeah, so this is something that

01:02:37.640 --> 01:02:44.360
[Guest]: I've usually been on the most cynical side of, which is that I feel like, that just as it is

01:02:44.360 --> 01:02:50.920
[Guest]: very difficult for news to penetrate bubbles, I feel I don't think that data journalism

01:02:51.480 --> 01:02:55.960
[Guest]: is in any way an exception to that. And now there's quite a range of, you know,

01:02:55.960 --> 01:03:03.400
[Guest]: ideologically tinted data journalism, quote unquote, available as well. If you want to share it on a

01:03:03.400 --> 01:03:08.520
[Guest]: WhatsApp group, you can find, you know, something that argues that the GDP is in great health,

01:03:08.520 --> 01:03:15.720
[Guest]: you'll find something written somewhere about it. So I've usually tended to, to not feel that I'm

01:03:16.280 --> 01:03:20.200
[Guest]: changing minds, that that's, that's not what's happening. I feel like I'm being, you know,

01:03:20.200 --> 01:03:27.320
[Guest]: maybe uncovering truths for people who want to read it, but not necessarily changing minds.

01:03:27.320 --> 01:03:34.680
[Guest]: But the more I think about it, the space, the position and the context of the people

01:03:35.640 --> 01:03:42.040
[Guest]: matters a lot when it comes to mind changing. So I don't think that we change people's minds in

01:03:42.040 --> 01:03:47.960
[Guest]: in terms of electoral outcomes, for example, you know, a lot of energy was invested,

01:03:47.960 --> 01:03:51.560
[Guest]: and I don't think it was wrong, because it was something that the numbers showed

01:03:51.560 --> 01:03:57.320
[Guest]: about the Gujarat model in 2014. So if data journalism worked, then data journalists

01:03:57.320 --> 01:04:02.440
[Guest]: conclusively showed the problems of the Gujarat model in 2014, and that is absolutely nothing.

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:09.000
[Guest]: So, you know, I think it's crazy to think any journalism has electoral impacts. And that

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:14.440
[Guest]: includes data journalism as well. Similarly, I feel like people don't like being called out

01:04:14.440 --> 01:04:21.720
[Guest]: and confronted on social media. And especially if they can find a large and noisy support group,

01:04:21.720 --> 01:04:29.800
[Guest]: they'll they'll shout even louder to not hear what you're saying. But the quieter and more

01:04:29.800 --> 01:04:37.640
[Guest]: intimate spaces are the ones in which I do feel that some of this percolates at some level. So,

01:04:37.640 --> 01:04:44.200
[Guest]: and you know, maybe it doesn't for things that matter. Maybe it doesn't for politics, for example,

01:04:44.200 --> 01:04:50.680
[Guest]: but I do think that things like, like, for example, demonetization, which, which in a way,

01:04:50.680 --> 01:04:57.080
[Guest]: after the election was won, people didn't have to worry any more that accepting that demonetization

01:04:57.080 --> 01:05:01.800
[Guest]: was a problem would derail the BJP's chances. Now they were not worried. Now the election had been

01:05:01.800 --> 01:05:09.560
[Guest]: won for BJP supporters, for example. So, in a quieter, one on one, more intimate context,

01:05:09.560 --> 01:05:20.200
[Guest]: I do feel that then people might consider the value of being shown or told numbers that don't

01:05:20.200 --> 01:05:29.320
[Guest]: necessarily, that uncover a true truth for them as well. I'm not a confrontational person. And I

01:05:29.320 --> 01:05:34.120
[Guest]: similarly feel this about the tone and the way in which these conversations need to

01:05:34.120 --> 01:05:40.040
[Guest]: happen as well. So, if we're only going to think of this in terms of changing people's

01:05:40.040 --> 01:05:45.000
[Guest]: minds in terms of party politics, then then we're not just going to feel cynical. It's just,

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:51.960
[Guest]: it's a lost cause. And if that is going to be the sort of igniting force for journalism,

01:05:51.960 --> 01:05:57.480
[Guest]: then that's that's just a hopeless enterprise. But if it is to try and think at a more human,

01:05:57.480 --> 01:06:05.800
[Guest]: human interaction level of this truly is what the numbers that I, in all fairness, have found,

01:06:05.800 --> 01:06:11.320
[Guest]: I don't need to beat you over the head about them. I don't need to show you that you were

01:06:11.880 --> 01:06:17.160
[Guest]: wrong to believe them. But here, here they are. And I don't feel like one needs to be very,

01:06:18.200 --> 01:06:24.200
[Guest]: that this sort of kindness needs to be extended to people who are say, casteist or, you know,

01:06:24.200 --> 01:06:29.640
[Guest]: anti-Muslim. It doesn't apply to all contexts. But when you are trying to change people's minds

01:06:29.640 --> 01:06:35.480
[Guest]: about say, you know, poverty numbers or health numbers, that sort of stuff, I would like to

01:06:35.480 --> 01:06:42.280
[Guest]: think that it gets somewhere. To think that it's going to make big societal changes. I don't see

01:06:42.280 --> 01:06:46.920
[Guest]: evidence of that happening. And I don't I don't know if that is journalism's project at all.

01:06:46.920 --> 01:06:51.880
[Amit Varma]: That's actually, you know, a fascinating note to continue on. But I mean, my aside there is that

01:06:51.880 --> 01:06:57.640
[Amit Varma]: I think that writers and public intellectuals and journalists might sometimes overestimate their

01:06:57.640 --> 01:07:02.760
[Amit Varma]: impact in the short run, but underestimate it in the long run. And I think therefore, what,

01:07:02.760 --> 01:07:07.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, we have to keep doing is just keep banging on and just leave that historical record

01:07:07.240 --> 01:07:14.920
[Amit Varma]: and just kind of make the task of those who come after us a little easier. You know, your last few

01:07:14.920 --> 01:07:19.080
[Amit Varma]: words when you were speaking about journalism's project, what is journalism's project? Because

01:07:19.080 --> 01:07:24.200
[Amit Varma]: on the one hand, there is an idealistic view that and a view which is dear to me in certain ways

01:07:24.200 --> 01:07:28.360
[Amit Varma]: that we must sort of kind of comfort the afflicted and afflict the comfortable as the cliche goes,

01:07:28.360 --> 01:07:32.520
[Amit Varma]: and journalists have a duty to keep questioning whoever is in power and all of that and all that

01:07:32.520 --> 01:07:37.080
[Amit Varma]: is fine. At the same time, there is another more pragmatic view that look at the end of the day,

01:07:37.080 --> 01:07:41.800
[Amit Varma]: you have to think of the market and every company has to make a profit, and blah, blah, blah. And

01:07:41.800 --> 01:07:48.200
[Amit Varma]: those are a different set of imperatives, which in some sense, are, you know, a little bit more

01:07:48.200 --> 01:07:53.400
[Amit Varma]: or less, are amoral. And more and more, what we find in the present time is that one, there is a

01:07:53.400 --> 01:07:58.040
[Amit Varma]: lot of journalism, which is going in one direction, which is saying that we will not question those

01:07:58.040 --> 01:08:02.440
[Amit Varma]: in power, because that could, that could affect our bottom line in many different ways. And two,

01:08:02.440 --> 01:08:07.160
[Amit Varma]: on the other hand, we have people who should just be reporters, just focus on facts, just maintain

01:08:07.160 --> 01:08:12.120
[Amit Varma]: the sort of balance between news and opinion, which once used to be sacrosanct, almost turning

01:08:12.120 --> 01:08:17.640
[Amit Varma]: into sort of journalistic activists, in a sense. And of course, the finest journalists that I read

01:08:17.640 --> 01:08:22.120
[Amit Varma]: do not do this at all. You know, their reporter speaks for themselves, people like you and Supriya

01:08:22.120 --> 01:08:27.080
[Amit Varma]: Sharma, and so many fine people, one could go on and on. But at the same time, there is in other

01:08:27.080 --> 01:08:33.240
[Amit Varma]: places, you see these little strains of sort of you can make out which side the journalist is on,

01:08:33.240 --> 01:08:38.680
[Guest]: so to say. What is journalism's project according to you? I do, I do spend a lot of time thinking

01:08:38.680 --> 01:08:48.120
[Guest]: about, you know, what do you call activists? I also try and think of it in terms of very, sort

01:08:48.120 --> 01:08:54.680
[Guest]: of very sort of engaged and involved kind of journalism, you know. And I try to think about

01:08:54.680 --> 01:09:01.720
[Guest]: why I have such discomfort with it, and whether if I wasn't wrapped in all the privilege that I am,

01:09:01.720 --> 01:09:09.240
[Guest]: I, maybe I too would be, would feel the need to be much more involved and angry about the things

01:09:09.800 --> 01:09:16.840
[Guest]: that I was talking about. I don't think journalism's project is unchanged. And I don't,

01:09:17.640 --> 01:09:24.200
[Guest]: you know, neither the political environment nor the financial environment, for me, changes

01:09:24.200 --> 01:09:31.960
[Guest]: that key project of beginning by questioning, holding those in power accountable, speaking

01:09:31.960 --> 01:09:39.400
[Guest]: truth to power, bringing forth the things that those in power seek to hide, you know, adding

01:09:40.840 --> 01:09:45.640
[Guest]: weight and courage to the people who are trying to talk about things that are being hidden,

01:09:45.640 --> 01:09:54.200
[Guest]: but also in bringing out just the, you know, how in news stories, people never sound like

01:09:54.200 --> 01:10:01.160
[Guest]: actual humans. They sound like either archetypes, or they sound like some sort of quote,

01:10:01.720 --> 01:10:10.360
[Guest]: bot, or nobody sounds like an actual human in a news story. So, part of journalism's project

01:10:10.360 --> 01:10:18.520
[Guest]: should also be the feeling of encountering people. And that happens not at all, because

01:10:18.520 --> 01:10:25.000
[Guest]: the most engaged and involved people aren't unafflicted by this. They too are reporting in

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:32.440
[Guest]: a way, talking to people in a way to push, you know, to make their own point admirable,

01:10:32.440 --> 01:10:41.400
[Guest]: though it may be forcefully, but without allowing people to be anything more than what that quote

01:10:41.400 --> 01:10:49.320
[Guest]: needs to be. So, I mean, I wish journalism project was a little more of all of that as well.

01:10:49.880 --> 01:10:57.640
[Guest]: You know, the joy that should be coming from it doesn't need to come from writing about purely

01:10:57.640 --> 01:11:09.640
[Guest]: joyful things. But that element of getting a window into just some, like a moment of humanity

01:11:10.360 --> 01:11:18.840
[Guest]: that doesn't necessarily need to be either bringing you to tears, or, you know, producing

01:11:18.840 --> 01:11:27.960
[Guest]: great, or, I haven't read a lot of Hindi books, but my extremely boring middle of the road, most,

01:11:27.960 --> 01:11:36.040
[Guest]: most favorite book is Raag Darbari. And I want more of Raag Darbari in journalism,

01:11:36.600 --> 01:11:41.640
[Guest]: not purely because you know, of all the ironies and all that it exposed, but also because

01:11:41.640 --> 01:11:48.520
[Guest]: nobody can tell you the plot of Raag Darbari. It is, it's a meandering journey of all sorts

01:11:48.520 --> 01:11:54.680
[Guest]: of human experience. And obviously, that cannot be what every news story does. But I wish there

01:11:54.680 --> 01:11:59.400
[Guest]: was more of that a bit of whimsy, a bit of, you know, people allowed to be a little more

01:12:00.280 --> 01:12:06.840
[Guest]: than what journalism's project requires them to be. Because there's no way to feel empathy

01:12:06.840 --> 01:12:12.920
[Guest]: or to feel, to see people as anything beyond the categories that journalists have decided

01:12:12.920 --> 01:12:19.800
[Guest]: they fit in. If we, if we don't report with, with anything beyond, you know, all of the while,

01:12:19.800 --> 01:12:26.840
[Guest]: all of my time in newsrooms, I never wrote more than 350 words per piece. And what that meant

01:12:26.840 --> 01:12:32.840
[Guest]: is that I had learned to switch off people so fast. I didn't want to know much more about them

01:12:32.840 --> 01:12:37.640
[Guest]: because there was nothing I could do with it. And one of the things that I would really, you know,

01:12:37.640 --> 01:12:42.680
[Guest]: want, even if you aren't in an organization, young journalists aren't in an organization that

01:12:42.680 --> 01:12:49.000
[Guest]: requires them to also take videos or whatever, I wish people would record people at length,

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:54.920
[Guest]: and not just keep it, you know, make something out of it, even if it's just for your family to

01:12:54.920 --> 01:13:00.360
[Guest]: listen to, but like, a long podcast of your conversation with someone who just made it to

01:13:00.360 --> 01:13:06.360
[Guest]: just made it to one single quote in your new story will, will lead you to, even if you're

01:13:06.360 --> 01:13:11.400
[Guest]: not able to write a Raag Dharbari into your news reporting, at least there's a Raag Dharbari in

01:13:11.400 --> 01:13:15.480
[Guest]: your mind, you know, your experiences are at least adding up to that.

01:13:15.480 --> 01:13:19.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, and I've just discovered that besides podcasts and Ferguson, we have a third thing in

01:13:19.480 --> 01:13:23.400
[Amit Varma]: common, which is our love for Raag Dharbari, which is, like you said, you can't describe it,

01:13:23.400 --> 01:13:27.800
[Amit Varma]: it's just such an incredible, capacious book, it contains so much, it's beautiful.

01:13:27.800 --> 01:13:31.480
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you were speaking with a long podcast. And, you know, that's one of

01:13:31.480 --> 01:13:35.240
[Amit Varma]: my personal frustrations that I'll read a great piece of journalism, and I'll

01:13:35.240 --> 01:13:39.160
[Amit Varma]: see these quotes in it. And I'll be like, shit that, you know, I wish I could listen to the

01:13:39.160 --> 01:13:43.160
[Amit Varma]: full thing. Like, I think some month during the conversation, I don't know if it was on record, or,

01:13:43.880 --> 01:13:49.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, when the tapes weren't rolling, as it were mentioned how many hours of sort of interviews

01:13:49.240 --> 01:13:53.960
[Amit Varma]: he has. And I'm like, I would like to listen to all of them. And similarly, while reading, you

01:13:53.960 --> 01:13:59.880
[Amit Varma]: know, my last episode was with the artist and historian Anshul Malhotra on her, you know,

01:13:59.880 --> 01:14:04.200
[Amit Varma]: the oral histories of partition, deeply moving book. And while reading that book, again, I wish

01:14:04.200 --> 01:14:09.480
[Amit Varma]: that my God that imagine being able to listen to these conversations. My next question sort of is

01:14:09.480 --> 01:14:15.880
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, that sort of what can often be a dichotomy, but should not be and the best

01:14:15.880 --> 01:14:22.040
[Amit Varma]: writers combine it very well, like you do, which is the two conflicting impulses that one, you want

01:14:22.040 --> 01:14:26.840
[Amit Varma]: the data to tell you the bigger story to give you the big picture. But at the same time, you want to

01:14:26.840 --> 01:14:31.880
[Amit Varma]: make it relatable, and you want to make it real and human as it were, by actually sort of telling

01:14:31.880 --> 01:14:38.440
[Amit Varma]: a story about it. And you know, and they can often sort of exist that sort of conflict where someone

01:14:38.440 --> 01:14:42.840
[Amit Varma]: who doesn't look at the bigger picture at all might be simplifying or might be, you know, not

01:14:42.840 --> 01:14:47.880
[Amit Varma]: getting anywhere close to the truth, while someone who is only focused on the big picture might be

01:14:47.880 --> 01:14:53.640
[Amit Varma]: able to communicate in abstract terms what the big picture is, but not make it so real and concrete

01:14:53.640 --> 01:14:58.280
[Amit Varma]: that the reader can empathize with it. And you know, in a lot of your writing, you kind of marry

01:14:58.280 --> 01:15:02.360
[Amit Varma]: these two, like, for example, I want to quote from this piece that you wrote in March, I think March

01:15:02.360 --> 01:15:08.840
[Amit Varma]: 23, in Al Jazeera about migrant workers, where you wrote, you began the piece by saying, quote,

01:15:08.840 --> 01:15:13.000
[Amit Varma]: on Saturday, the 50th day since India's first Coronavirus case was confirmed,

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Parma Bhandari called his family in Nepal to reassure them that he would be coming home.

01:15:17.320 --> 01:15:22.040
[Amit Varma]: They were not all going to die without seeing each other, he told them, stop quote, which is such a

01:15:22.040 --> 01:15:26.520
[Amit Varma]: lovely human beginning and immediately makes the reader interested. And then you there's a lot of

01:15:26.520 --> 01:15:32.040
[Amit Varma]: data in the piece, but very relatable. And then towards the end, we have the line where, you know,

01:15:32.040 --> 01:15:36.920
[Amit Varma]: you quote his roommate, Padam Bhandari saying, quote, now there is no going back, whatever it

01:15:36.920 --> 01:15:42.040
[Amit Varma]: is, we have to face it here, stop quote. And this is from an aspect that you discussed in, you know,

01:15:42.040 --> 01:15:47.240
[Amit Varma]: episode five of the Moving Curve, your amazing podcast, which we go on to discuss. But here again,

01:15:47.240 --> 01:15:53.240
[Amit Varma]: it seems that you've, you know, managed beautifully to marry the personal with the overarching, you

01:15:53.240 --> 01:15:58.360
[Amit Varma]: know, what's happening in general. So is this something that you've thought about a lot that,

01:15:58.360 --> 01:16:02.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, how do we marry these two aspects? Does it sometimes become conflicting in some ways?

01:16:03.400 --> 01:16:10.200
[Guest]: So it's actually one of the things that I don't feel that I do very well. It's partly on account

01:16:10.200 --> 01:16:15.640
[Guest]: of circumstance and partly on account of having just not figured out yet, not being sure yet,

01:16:15.640 --> 01:16:21.880
[Guest]: both in what I read and what I write, what, where I want, what I think the sweet spot is. So,

01:16:23.320 --> 01:16:29.400
[Guest]: you know, when I think about what should be ideal journalism, or what should be the ideal

01:16:29.400 --> 01:16:35.240
[Guest]: journalism that I'm doing, I would usually want to say to myself, I should be doing more travel,

01:16:35.240 --> 01:16:40.360
[Guest]: I should be going out and meeting more people. But partly, as you know, on account of the

01:16:40.360 --> 01:16:46.440
[Guest]: circumstances of my life right now, that's not, that's not something I do much now much, much

01:16:46.440 --> 01:16:52.600
[Guest]: less than I did before I used to, I got the opportunity to really see a lot of the country

01:16:52.600 --> 01:17:00.600
[Guest]: and learn a lot that way. So I don't think I do that. And I don't know how much more of it I want

01:17:00.600 --> 01:17:05.240
[Guest]: in both what I read and what I write. So the example I was giving you earlier about Canary,

01:17:05.240 --> 01:17:12.040
[Guest]: which is that it's a staggering piece of journalism, it's, you know, model for looking

01:17:12.040 --> 01:17:20.120
[Guest]: into corroboration of accusations. So I suppose if I, you know, the reporter should feel,

01:17:20.120 --> 01:17:25.800
[Guest]: the journalist should feel very proud of, of all of that, the humanising, the larger story,

01:17:25.800 --> 01:17:31.160
[Guest]: the narrative, all of that. But then, as I told you, I felt it fell deeply short on the

01:17:31.880 --> 01:17:37.560
[Guest]: data part of it, that was a necessary link, I think, to make the point that it sought to be

01:17:37.560 --> 01:17:45.240
[Guest]: making. So, you know, I should have felt that that that story was a triumph, but I didn't

01:17:45.240 --> 01:17:52.840
[Guest]: ultimately feel that. And then would I have been happier with not a seven part podcast, but a one,

01:17:52.840 --> 01:17:59.880
[Guest]: one, you know, 2000 word Washington Post piece that did actually manage to get at the heart of

01:17:59.880 --> 01:18:05.240
[Guest]: the judge's record, and then mention the allegations as well? Perhaps that's what I,

01:18:05.240 --> 01:18:11.560
[Guest]: you know, I'm looking more for. The trouble is that I find it very hard to think of examples of

01:18:12.360 --> 01:18:18.360
[Guest]: news reports where I felt that, you know, the narrative and the elements of storytelling that

01:18:18.360 --> 01:18:24.120
[Guest]: it brought to it, brought in something to the news story, to the story that, to me,

01:18:25.080 --> 01:18:28.920
[Guest]: would have otherwise, you know, I would have otherwise felt that it didn't give me what I

01:18:28.920 --> 01:18:36.200
[Guest]: wanted from it. I'm well aware that I have a much more involved way of looking at data stories. And

01:18:36.200 --> 01:18:41.080
[Guest]: it's probably, so one of the things I wanted to mention earlier to which I forgot, which is that

01:18:42.040 --> 01:18:46.360
[Guest]: the way maths is taught in this country is such a disgrace on the whole,

01:18:46.360 --> 01:18:53.080
[Guest]: mainly because it makes people feel that they can't do it for very unfair and often discriminatory

01:18:53.080 --> 01:18:59.720
[Guest]: reasons. And I feel very bad when I occasionally take data journalism courses to see very bright

01:18:59.720 --> 01:19:06.040
[Guest]: people completely freeze at, you know, very simple numbers, 20 year olds who get absolutely

01:19:06.040 --> 01:19:14.680
[Guest]: frightened by simple percentage or subtraction. And I, you know, imagine that people who have

01:19:14.680 --> 01:19:20.040
[Guest]: been taught maths similarly feel the same when they see a data story. So, you know, that's the

01:19:20.040 --> 01:19:26.040
[Guest]: last sort of thing that I would be, that I want readers to feel. So maybe, maybe more of this

01:19:26.680 --> 01:19:31.720
[Guest]: is important to not make, I don't want readers to ever have to feel that here's someone saying

01:19:31.720 --> 01:19:38.040
[Guest]: something very smart. And because I am, I don't understand numbers, I'm not smart enough. And

01:19:38.040 --> 01:19:43.800
[Guest]: that's why I haven't understood what they're saying. So, you know, maybe sacrificing some of

01:19:43.800 --> 01:19:50.680
[Guest]: the charts and the numbers to be able to tell the story better would not alienate people who have

01:19:50.680 --> 01:19:59.480
[Guest]: not been, just not had the opportunity to study math or logic in a way that would help them.

01:19:59.480 --> 01:20:05.560
[Guest]: Because having not been trained in statistics myself, the level of statistical analysis I do

01:20:05.560 --> 01:20:11.560
[Guest]: is extremely basic. And in a way, you know, that holds me back from being able to do more ambitious

01:20:11.560 --> 01:20:16.280
[Guest]: stuff, but I would hope that it makes it more accessible to readers who are more likely to be

01:20:16.280 --> 01:20:22.280
[Guest]: at my level than at, you know, regression analysis level. Sorry, I got a bit lost over there.

01:20:24.040 --> 01:20:27.640
[Amit Varma]: No, all of it made sense. And all of it sort of spoke to my question about,

01:20:28.360 --> 01:20:32.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, the trade off between narrative and data, the big picture in the concrete.

01:20:32.920 --> 01:20:39.560
[Guest]: Yeah. So occasionally I see people who do it wonderfully. I was reading recently a

01:20:39.560 --> 01:20:47.800
[Guest]: ProPublica investigation into Chicago's first hundred COVID deaths. And here there was original

01:20:47.800 --> 01:20:55.160
[Guest]: data journalism because there had been no analysis yet by, you know, either the local administration

01:20:55.160 --> 01:20:58.520
[Guest]: or the government. So this is something that journalism needed to do, because I think they

01:20:58.520 --> 01:21:03.080
[Guest]: found something like 70 out of the hundred deaths were African-Americans. So that was

01:21:03.080 --> 01:21:07.560
[Guest]: an important thing to get to quickly because that was still at a stage at which, you know,

01:21:07.560 --> 01:21:14.840
[Guest]: the medical fraternity could rejig and rethink. And it begins with a very moving story as well.

01:21:14.840 --> 01:21:20.840
[Guest]: And what I liked is what it, you know, centered on the point that African-Americans are much more

01:21:20.840 --> 01:21:27.400
[Guest]: likely to have what are known as comorbidities for COVID, but that doesn't make these deaths

01:21:27.400 --> 01:21:33.560
[Guest]: inevitable. And just sometimes you read a line and you're just like, why was I thinking,

01:21:33.560 --> 01:21:38.680
[Guest]: this is what I was thinking. Someone has called me out. You know, making morbidity sound like

01:21:38.680 --> 01:21:45.640
[Guest]: inevitability is something I was doing. And I read that one line and it just made me feel like,

01:21:45.640 --> 01:21:50.680
[Guest]: OK, this is something I should keep in mind when I'm reporting about Indian COVID numbers as well.

01:21:50.680 --> 01:21:59.240
[Guest]: So that was, you know, to me, one of those examples of really being drawn in by the narrative

01:21:59.240 --> 01:22:05.320
[Guest]: and then being kept there by the original, truly original data work over there. But

01:22:07.080 --> 01:22:11.080
[Guest]: yeah, I suppose this is where knowing your audience becomes important. And I don't know

01:22:11.080 --> 01:22:17.560
[Guest]: my audience at all. So knowing how much more storytelling my audience would like is a vague

01:22:17.560 --> 01:22:24.840
[Guest]: sort of guess that I make. Like at The Hindu, for example, there were a lot of young students

01:22:24.840 --> 01:22:30.520
[Guest]: who read the newspaper and I know that they were really hungry for information. So I did want to

01:22:30.520 --> 01:22:35.880
[Guest]: speak to them very much. I love that audience. And I think they were OK with not having the

01:22:36.760 --> 01:22:42.040
[Guest]: storytelling elements. They really wanted to get to the meat of it. So I don't know,

01:22:42.040 --> 01:22:45.800
[Guest]: maybe I hope at some point I can figure out what my audience wants.

01:22:45.800 --> 01:22:49.400
[Amit Varma]: There's something you said earlier, which I think is profoundly important and I feel

01:22:49.400 --> 01:22:53.560
[Amit Varma]: strongly about it. So I'll kind of underscore that, which is, you know, when you pointed out

01:22:53.560 --> 01:22:58.600
[Amit Varma]: that people who may not have studied math very well and they might come across a story they don't

01:22:58.600 --> 01:23:03.560
[Amit Varma]: really understand and they feel that, oh, am I the stupid one here? And, you know, I sort of teach

01:23:03.560 --> 01:23:07.960
[Amit Varma]: this online writing course where I constantly tell them that, look, if your reader doesn't

01:23:07.960 --> 01:23:11.960
[Amit Varma]: understand something, it's not their fault, it's your fault. You know, and I think that's true of

01:23:11.960 --> 01:23:16.040
[Amit Varma]: journalists as well, that, you know, do not condescend to your readers. And, you know,

01:23:16.040 --> 01:23:20.840
[Amit Varma]: if any reader doesn't understand something, you have messed up. That person is not stupid.

01:23:20.840 --> 01:23:26.360
[Amit Varma]: And I think that, you know, that basic level of respect for the reader is not something that

01:23:26.360 --> 01:23:32.040
[Amit Varma]: writers are mindful of. And now if we get into these reflexive habits of using jargon and opaque

01:23:32.040 --> 01:23:36.680
[Amit Varma]: prose and all of that, and we're not really thinking about sort of the reader's experience.

01:23:36.680 --> 01:23:41.480
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, and I guess for a data journalist that there must also be that tussle, right?

01:23:41.480 --> 01:23:45.240
[Amit Varma]: Because in the sense that you don't want to dumb anything down, you want to say what you have to

01:23:45.240 --> 01:23:49.720
[Amit Varma]: say, but at the same time, you have a lot of complex things you want to say, you want it to

01:23:49.720 --> 01:23:55.080
[Amit Varma]: be understood. Is that sort of a tussle that you faced internally? So, I think what's very useful

01:23:55.080 --> 01:24:03.160
[Guest]: for me here is not having statistical skills myself. So, there isn't very far that I can go

01:24:03.160 --> 01:24:11.720
[Guest]: with it myself. So, I do think that that helps keep all of what I write at a level that's,

01:24:12.360 --> 01:24:16.120
[Guest]: you know, going to be manageable for the lay reader and probably too little for,

01:24:16.120 --> 01:24:23.480
[Guest]: say, many mid-readers who would be able to understand much more complex statistical

01:24:23.480 --> 01:24:28.360
[Guest]: concepts that I'm not actually familiar with. I think a lot of data journalism is trying to

01:24:28.360 --> 01:24:33.400
[Guest]: figure out where to stand on this. And you realize immediately when someone is being,

01:24:33.960 --> 01:24:39.800
[Guest]: is showboating. It's profoundly annoying to see in data journalism. It's, you know,

01:24:39.800 --> 01:24:47.160
[Guest]: not necessary in the least. And I suppose part of growing up is realizing how annoying

01:24:48.680 --> 01:24:54.600
[Guest]: FiveThirtyEight and Nate Silver are. You go into data journalism thinking,

01:24:54.600 --> 01:24:58.440
[Guest]: oh, this is what it's supposed to be like. Oh, my God, I can't believe I discovered Excel

01:24:58.440 --> 01:25:04.760
[Guest]: yesterday. And then after a few months of it, I'm so pleased I can't do anything beyond

01:25:04.760 --> 01:25:10.680
[Guest]: addition and subtraction on Excel, because if I'm going to start sounding like this,

01:25:11.960 --> 01:25:17.880
[Guest]: I mean, it has its own readership. It would be ridiculous for me to have a value judgment on

01:25:17.880 --> 01:25:25.000
[Guest]: something that is so, does so well, is so successful. But I can't stand to read most

01:25:25.000 --> 01:25:32.200
[Guest]: of it. I can't stand the tone. I can't stand the place at which it sits. And in Indian journalism,

01:25:32.200 --> 01:25:36.520
[Guest]: occasionally there's some of that, very rarely. The other thing that tends to happen now is that

01:25:37.080 --> 01:25:42.200
[Guest]: there's a great confusion between data visualization and data journalism.

01:25:42.200 --> 01:25:47.960
[Guest]: So what you'll occasionally see are wildly indulgent and extremely expensive data

01:25:47.960 --> 01:25:55.880
[Guest]: visualization efforts that involve very little journalism, actually. So that's another,

01:25:55.880 --> 01:26:03.640
[Guest]: that's another sort of, you know, someone with mad skills, who has been given a long rope by

01:26:03.640 --> 01:26:08.600
[Guest]: an editor, you can see that happening. And you can see, you can see a big budget being,

01:26:09.240 --> 01:26:14.760
[Guest]: being burned, sometimes for pretty, for a pretty modest outcome.

01:26:14.760 --> 01:26:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And I guess that's a natural journey for, you know, young people to make when they come into

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:22.760
[Amit Varma]: the profession. Like I remember when I was a young writer, I also like to showboat in my writing,

01:26:22.760 --> 01:26:27.160
[Amit Varma]: right? So has a fancy phrase and all that. And it's as you go along that journey that you realize,

01:26:27.160 --> 01:26:31.400
[Amit Varma]: as the saying goes, that you have to kill your darlings, and you have to put the reader up front,

01:26:31.400 --> 01:26:36.280
[Amit Varma]: it's not about showing how smart you are. And I guess data journalists make the same question.

01:26:36.280 --> 01:26:40.200
[Amit Varma]: My next question sort of harks back to something we were discussing earlier about how, you know,

01:26:40.200 --> 01:26:46.440
[Amit Varma]: that as you kind of started, you know, discovering the uses of data and what it can be for your frame

01:26:46.440 --> 01:26:52.760
[Amit Varma]: also subtly shifts in the way you kind of, you know, look at things shifts. Now, I would imagine

01:26:52.760 --> 01:26:57.000
[Amit Varma]: that I mean, one, would you agree that at some level, every journalist needs to be a data

01:26:57.000 --> 01:27:01.800
[Amit Varma]: journalist, not in the sense of knowing all the tech and doing all the Excel and all of that,

01:27:01.800 --> 01:27:06.840
[Amit Varma]: but just in terms of understanding the bigger picture, through numbers and all of that. So

01:27:06.840 --> 01:27:11.640
[Amit Varma]: that's part one of the question. And, and part two, then is that, you know, in all your years

01:27:11.640 --> 01:27:16.920
[Amit Varma]: of experience, where you've both reported and looked at data and all of that, you know, can you,

01:27:16.920 --> 01:27:22.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, simply put, what about India do journalists not understand that they would,

01:27:22.680 --> 01:27:29.160
[Guest]: if they had an adequate understanding of data? Okay, um, let me get to the first one. And then

01:27:29.160 --> 01:27:35.640
[Guest]: let me slowly let the second one marinate in my brain. I'd say that a lot of what I did for the

01:27:35.640 --> 01:27:43.480
[Guest]: first few years of what I looked at as a data journalism specific job is actually what all

01:27:43.480 --> 01:27:51.000
[Guest]: journalists should be doing. It was not specialized at all. And anyone with, you know, for Saturday's

01:27:51.000 --> 01:27:56.440
[Guest]: training should be able to do that stuff. And absolutely, all journalists should be able to

01:27:56.440 --> 01:28:02.760
[Guest]: incorporate a certain amount of data into all the news reporting. This applies deeply to political

01:28:02.760 --> 01:28:10.760
[Guest]: journalists, it applies, you know, very deeply to crime reporters about, and I have some, you know,

01:28:10.760 --> 01:28:16.280
[Guest]: very strong feelings about crime reporting in this country, which I think is a, is an absolute,

01:28:16.920 --> 01:28:22.840
[Guest]: it's truly dangerous and destructive, not just about the people who, you know, are reported on,

01:28:22.840 --> 01:28:28.120
[Guest]: it's just that so much of our understanding of the country about crime, about, you know,

01:28:28.120 --> 01:28:37.160
[Guest]: relationships, about so much of everything is colored by the fact that a large part of

01:28:37.160 --> 01:28:47.240
[Guest]: crime reporting in this country is a crime reporter uncritically reproducing an FIR as fact.

01:28:48.200 --> 01:28:57.240
[Guest]: And an FIR is not fact. An FIR is one person's attempt at storytelling mediated by a deeply

01:28:57.240 --> 01:29:04.840
[Guest]: involved and deeply problematic police system. And that's the basis on which we form so much of our

01:29:05.480 --> 01:29:11.160
[Guest]: understanding of this country. It really worries me. And there's not been any reckoning around

01:29:11.160 --> 01:29:15.880
[Guest]: crime reporting at all in this country, despite so much momentous stuff around crime having

01:29:15.880 --> 01:29:23.240
[Guest]: happened in the last seven, eight years. So yes, I really don't know why Moon Newsroom don't do

01:29:23.240 --> 01:29:28.600
[Guest]: this. It's really quite, it's relatively cheap. It's easy to do now. Everyone has a data journalist

01:29:28.600 --> 01:29:35.080
[Guest]: on their rolls anyway, to just give reporters the training themselves. Again, a lot of news

01:29:35.080 --> 01:29:42.840
[Guest]: reporters would be afraid of numbers. So, you know, maybe it's harder to get through on that.

01:29:42.840 --> 01:29:50.200
[Guest]: Even working in teams is so rare between data journalists and other journalists. So yes,

01:29:50.200 --> 01:29:55.960
[Guest]: absolutely. I mean, hopefully we'll reach a point where desks start returning reports,

01:29:55.960 --> 01:30:02.040
[Guest]: news reports that don't have any sort of references to data or research to substantiate

01:30:02.040 --> 01:30:07.320
[Guest]: at least the key point that the article is making, or at least the fact, you know, just as you need

01:30:07.320 --> 01:30:12.120
[Guest]: to be able to tell your editor who your anonymous source is most of the time and why you've not

01:30:12.120 --> 01:30:17.000
[Guest]: quoted them, you should be able to at least assure your editor that the arguments that

01:30:17.000 --> 01:30:23.160
[Guest]: your anecdotes are making are sort of supported by what research says. And you know, that should

01:30:23.160 --> 01:30:29.240
[Guest]: be a sort of line that you need to benchmark that you need to achieve for a story to go forward.

01:30:29.800 --> 01:30:35.160
[Guest]: So yeah, I think it's really inexpensive. And I hope more energy is put into that. And the other

01:30:35.160 --> 01:30:39.960
[Guest]: thing is, you know, most journalists, especially younger journalists, and especially in non

01:30:39.960 --> 01:30:49.080
[Guest]: glamorous beats, are so under trained, under resourced, under focused on, you know,

01:30:50.200 --> 01:30:59.320
[Guest]: they deserve it, they deserve being given these skills. And frequently, you know, I get other

01:30:59.320 --> 01:31:04.840
[Guest]: people getting in touch with me and from non English media, where really, I feel like the

01:31:04.840 --> 01:31:13.640
[Guest]: hunger and the desire to have data journalistic stories in the paper is so enormous, and such an

01:31:13.640 --> 01:31:20.280
[Guest]: unmet need that nobody is able to still fill this gap at all. So I wrote for a while for,

01:31:21.080 --> 01:31:25.160
[Guest]: I mean, I say I wrote, but I wrote for a while for Denik Bhaskar. And I just,

01:31:25.160 --> 01:31:29.720
[Guest]: they just said, just write in English, and we will translate it and carry it because,

01:31:29.720 --> 01:31:38.280
[Guest]: you know, just be mindful of roughly who our audience is. So you know, they don't write

01:31:38.280 --> 01:31:45.080
[Guest]: completely sort of a Tamil Nadu, Kerala story. But yeah, I mean, the problem is that most non

01:31:45.080 --> 01:31:50.760
[Guest]: English media can't pay very well. So that's immediately a problem. But yes, I wish all

01:31:50.760 --> 01:31:56.360
[Guest]: journalists could get some of these resources and all non English media in particular could be given

01:31:56.360 --> 01:32:01.800
[Amit Varma]: some of these resources. What is the second thing? Yeah, my second thing, I mean, before we get to

01:32:01.800 --> 01:32:07.240
[Amit Varma]: that first, I guess, you know, the Arushi Talwar case, or the way the SSR in Braglio was reported

01:32:07.240 --> 01:32:11.800
[Amit Varma]: would be prime examples of, you know, how horrendous the crime reporting in our countries

01:32:11.800 --> 01:32:18.120
[Amit Varma]: is it partly because, I mean, do we take shortcuts, because we are also understaffed in the sense that,

01:32:18.120 --> 01:32:22.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, people except in places like caravan and so on, people don't really get 10 days to

01:32:22.680 --> 01:32:28.440
[Amit Varma]: work on one story. And, you know, let the let it marinate talk to 15 sources. Instead, everything

01:32:28.440 --> 01:32:32.600
[Amit Varma]: is like, okay, where's your story for the day? And, and therefore, you take these shortcuts. And

01:32:32.600 --> 01:32:37.560
[Guest]: that's just how the system works. Yeah, there is that. But I mean, that's a feature of it. And

01:32:37.560 --> 01:32:46.200
[Guest]: that's not, you know, an entirely all encompassing explanation as such. So in Mumbai, for example,

01:32:46.200 --> 01:32:52.040
[Guest]: where just as in Delhi, the crime reporting is an extremely competitive beat over there,

01:32:52.040 --> 01:32:57.720
[Guest]: a crime reporter would easily have five, six stories available to file every day. So,

01:32:58.520 --> 01:33:04.120
[Guest]: you know, they're not short on the stories to file, they don't necessarily need to file all

01:33:04.120 --> 01:33:11.000
[Guest]: of them, they have enough stuff always. No, it's just that we've made this, and editors know this

01:33:11.000 --> 01:33:16.200
[Guest]: very well, because, you know, most editors are very friendly with senior police as well.

01:33:16.200 --> 01:33:25.160
[Guest]: We've just made this an acceptable form of journalism. Most beginning crime reporters, your job is to go hang around the police station and then faithfully report

01:33:25.160 --> 01:33:31.160
[Guest]: whatever the key FIRs of that day are. We haven't gone into it. You know, asking someone to take

01:33:31.160 --> 01:33:35.320
[Guest]: 10 days and corroborate from multiple places is another thing. We haven't even said get,

01:33:35.960 --> 01:33:41.240
[Guest]: if you're reporting on an FIR, speak to the complainant. We haven't even started from there.

01:33:41.240 --> 01:33:48.440
[Guest]: Let the accused person get their side of it. We've made it an acceptable practice for just the FIR to

01:33:48.440 --> 01:33:55.880
[Guest]: become a statement of fact. So, yeah, in the high profile ones, we saw that, but you know,

01:33:56.920 --> 01:34:01.480
[Guest]: when I was at the Times of India in Mumbai, there was a shift thing that used to come to us every

01:34:01.480 --> 01:34:05.720
[Guest]: few weeks, which is that you would have to be the day shift reporter or the night shift reporter,

01:34:05.720 --> 01:34:09.560
[Guest]: no matter what your regular beat was, you'd have to do it in rotation every few weeks, which is

01:34:09.560 --> 01:34:15.000
[Guest]: your job would be to, basically in Mumbai, if a building fell down, you'd have to go and cover it

01:34:15.000 --> 01:34:19.320
[Guest]: because you know, that happens all the time. So who are you going to assign? You can't have a

01:34:19.320 --> 01:34:23.960
[Guest]: building falling down reporter. You need to assign someone who's just free to do the running around

01:34:23.960 --> 01:34:28.360
[Guest]: for the day. And your job was to call key police stations every few hours and check what's

01:34:28.360 --> 01:34:36.200
[Guest]: happening. The fire department, you know, in no way have we made it, you know, when I used to see

01:34:36.200 --> 01:34:40.040
[Guest]: when I used to see those briefs that would come in from the cops also, there was just stuff that

01:34:40.040 --> 01:34:44.360
[Guest]: was clearly an issue, or you could see that it was a script because you'd, this is one of the

01:34:44.360 --> 01:34:52.360
[Guest]: things I find a lot in even in reporting on court judgments is that cops in India follow a script

01:34:52.360 --> 01:34:59.800
[Guest]: so regularly about for a particular IPC section. So, for example, on suicides in Mumbai, I remember

01:34:59.800 --> 01:35:08.600
[Guest]: on this press notes, they would regularly say, Azarpanala Kantaloon, which is tired of his

01:35:08.600 --> 01:35:13.720
[Guest]: illness. And you'd immediately think, wow, you know, I'm sure there's more to it, maybe the

01:35:13.720 --> 01:35:20.840
[Guest]: person couldn't pay for it, or, you know, Kantaloon means almost like a board of something.

01:35:21.720 --> 01:35:29.080
[Guest]: And so what was it? Was it was it? What illness was this? Was it TB? Are people still having to

01:35:29.080 --> 01:35:35.240
[Guest]: kill themselves? You know, as people still being driven to suicide by TB? Was it what illnesses

01:35:35.240 --> 01:35:41.160
[Guest]: are bankrupting people? There's so much more that needed to come out of that. But, you know, yeah,

01:35:41.160 --> 01:35:45.640
[Guest]: that that's how it was reported by the cops and then duly and faithfully reported by crime

01:35:45.640 --> 01:35:51.240
[Guest]: reporters as well. Even the the sexual assault investigation that I ended up doing in Delhi's

01:35:51.240 --> 01:35:58.280
[Guest]: district courts came out of regular reading in the newspapers in the days after the 2012

01:35:58.280 --> 01:36:08.040
[Guest]: Delhi rape. Regularly reading, a girl was kidnapped in a busy market and given a sedative-laced

01:36:08.040 --> 01:36:13.560
[Guest]: cold drink. And I started seeing this so often, or pulled into a moving car. I started seeing this

01:36:13.560 --> 01:36:18.040
[Guest]: so often, I really started wondering about this sedative-laced cold drink. Like, is it an issue?

01:36:18.040 --> 01:36:23.000
[Guest]: Should we now be careful that, you know, there's some sort of adulteration and cold drinks going

01:36:23.000 --> 01:36:28.440
[Guest]: on? And this moving car business at that time, you know, I lived with flatmates in Delhi. It

01:36:28.440 --> 01:36:33.320
[Guest]: used to terrify my mother to think that there are these moving cars just constantly pulling people

01:36:33.320 --> 01:36:40.760
[Guest]: and girls into cars. So that's what, I mean, looking into it came as a result of me myself

01:36:40.760 --> 01:36:47.560
[Guest]: making my own assessments about Delhi and my own safety from newspaper articles that were essentially

01:36:47.560 --> 01:36:55.240
[Guest]: faithfully reproducing FIRs. That, it turned out, had much more to do with parental criminalization

01:36:55.240 --> 01:37:02.200
[Guest]: of consensual, often inter-religious and inter-caste relationships than anything else.

01:37:02.760 --> 01:37:08.840
[Guest]: And it was such a fundamental disservice to everything, to the city itself, that this kind

01:37:08.840 --> 01:37:13.400
[Guest]: of reporting was forming the basis of our judgments about everything. I mean, I felt that maybe I

01:37:13.400 --> 01:37:18.120
[Guest]: felt that maybe I shouldn't be going out that much. Maybe I shouldn't be living in Delhi anymore.

01:37:18.120 --> 01:37:23.240
[Guest]: That's what started me looking at it and reporting on it at all.

01:37:23.880 --> 01:37:27.800
[Amit Varma]: So they weren't moving cars. So this was basically parents are pissed off that their daughter is

01:37:27.800 --> 01:37:32.440
[Amit Varma]: going in for an inter-religious or whatever, and then they file a case and then the FIR has

01:37:32.440 --> 01:37:35.160
[Amit Varma]: moving car. Wow, that's incredible. Okay, so my larger...

01:37:35.160 --> 01:37:40.120
[Guest]: The sedative-laced cold drink was usually the hallmark of that because you needed to say

01:37:40.120 --> 01:37:45.160
[Guest]: how this boy was able to kidnap her from a crowded market, there was a sedative-laced cold drink.

01:37:45.160 --> 01:37:52.520
[Guest]: So that's where... And there was, I looked at 650 cases in all and I can't remember how many

01:37:52.520 --> 01:37:59.000
[Guest]: had sedative-laced cold drinks in them. Many. No cop was able to produce a single cold drink

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:05.960
[Guest]: bottle in court, in even one. It was just complete fabrication from beginning to end,

01:38:05.960 --> 01:38:11.720
[Guest]: that part. The cold drink part was a complete 100% fabrication in all of those. It was just,

01:38:12.760 --> 01:38:18.360
[Guest]: I mean, the level of it was just appalling. I mean, it's pretty mind-blowing. I mean,

01:38:18.360 --> 01:38:22.600
[Amit Varma]: imagine the first person to put that in an FIR, you know, at least there you got to give them

01:38:22.600 --> 01:38:27.720
[Amit Varma]: some credit for imagination and, you know, becomes a meme. So perhaps must have been

01:38:27.720 --> 01:38:32.760
[Amit Varma]: some Tamilian gentleman who made it a meme and, you know, as you point out their talent for that.

01:38:32.760 --> 01:38:36.280
[Amit Varma]: So the larger question, which actually I want to make even larger and I want to kind of take

01:38:36.280 --> 01:38:41.160
[Amit Varma]: data out of it because, you know, you've been a journalist for so long and have seen the whole

01:38:41.160 --> 01:38:45.880
[Amit Varma]: industry so intimately. And my question simply is this, what about India do journalists not

01:38:45.880 --> 01:38:52.200
[Guest]: understand? So my favorite way to think about this is through elections. I love elections,

01:38:52.200 --> 01:38:57.160
[Guest]: I love opinion polling around it, I love the news reporting around it, even though it drives me

01:38:57.160 --> 01:39:02.360
[Guest]: crazy. And at least, you know, when I think about elections, the thing that journalists do not get

01:39:02.360 --> 01:39:10.200
[Guest]: is that the motivations that people believe drive them are often not the motivations that

01:39:10.200 --> 01:39:18.360
[Guest]: truly drive them. They are not trying to lie or obfuscate at all. It's just that

01:39:19.880 --> 01:39:28.920
[Guest]: most people, especially upper-caste people, do not get how central self-respect is to Indians.

01:39:28.920 --> 01:39:33.880
[Guest]: I think this has come home to me more and more in Tamil Nadu, but what's come home to me is not

01:39:34.760 --> 01:39:39.880
[Guest]: how much Tamils value self-respect, which they do, and which has, you know, a rich political

01:39:39.880 --> 01:39:44.920
[Guest]: history here, but it's also brought home to me the fact that so much of what I was seeing in

01:39:44.920 --> 01:39:51.320
[Guest]: the country was an expression of self-respect. Shankar, my boss at the Times of India,

01:39:51.320 --> 01:39:58.840
[Guest]: always told me that he felt that every election was, and every campaign, every political party,

01:39:58.840 --> 01:40:06.360
[Guest]: was about ideas. No matter how these narratives get set about this is an election of this,

01:40:06.360 --> 01:40:12.120
[Guest]: this is an election of rejection of that, they are very much about ideas. And now there's strong

01:40:12.120 --> 01:40:18.040
[Guest]: evidence for this. Rahul Rahman, Pradeep Chhabra have a superb book on ideology in Indian politics,

01:40:18.040 --> 01:40:24.760
[Guest]: and it's exactly, in a sense, what Shankar had felt about elections, which is that Indians are

01:40:24.760 --> 01:40:31.720
[Guest]: deeply ideological, most of them, and these are ideologically coherent positions, they change

01:40:31.720 --> 01:40:38.040
[Guest]: very little over time, and these positions are getting stronger. So, I don't think people realize

01:40:38.040 --> 01:40:45.320
[Guest]: how much ideas and ideology matter to people, and this is not just in elections now, I want to say.

01:40:45.320 --> 01:40:53.720
[Guest]: This applies, I feel this even when people talk about finance and about, well, household finance

01:40:53.720 --> 01:41:01.080
[Guest]: and poverty, which is failing to understand the motivations for why people spend money on the

01:41:01.080 --> 01:41:10.360
[Guest]: things they do is also a big issue with how people fail to understand so much of the economy.

01:41:10.360 --> 01:41:19.480
[Guest]: You know, feeling that, when people talk about spending on marriages as a social evil,

01:41:20.200 --> 01:41:27.640
[Guest]: and then, you know, so all of this comes down to pride, self-respect, and the power of ideas.

01:41:27.640 --> 01:41:34.200
[Guest]: And it doesn't take more than 10 minutes of involved talking to anybody, to be, to anybody,

01:41:34.200 --> 01:41:42.840
[Guest]: to any Indian, to be so struck by, to feel so struck by how deeply they hold ideas. And it's

01:41:42.840 --> 01:41:48.280
[Guest]: just that, just as you and I, you know, anyone who tries to talk to us in an involved way will

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:58.120
[Guest]: feel our passion for our ideas quickly, it just takes that extra, it takes that belief that people

01:41:58.120 --> 01:42:05.160
[Guest]: are more than what you've decided that they are. And so, in some ways, I'm glad that now I cover

01:42:05.160 --> 01:42:10.520
[Guest]: elections largely through data, because there is no way I would be able to translate into words

01:42:11.240 --> 01:42:19.000
[Guest]: how much of electoral motivation comes from, you know, the desire to be seen as a worthy human.

01:42:19.560 --> 01:42:25.000
[Guest]: And this does explain a lot of why people vote along cast lines, and it's not for the reasons

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:32.040
[Guest]: that you, that usually get reported as well. It explains, you know, party commitments.

01:42:32.040 --> 01:42:38.440
[Guest]: So yeah, you know, you'll always find this, right? And if you decide to engage in a conversation

01:42:38.440 --> 01:42:45.720
[Guest]: with anyone, it's always exciting to discover someone's passion, right? You don't expect

01:42:46.840 --> 01:42:52.040
[Guest]: that your Ola driver is deeply passionate about a movie star, or about, you know,

01:42:52.040 --> 01:43:01.480
[Guest]: a singer. Sometimes I've been in cabs in Chennai and been so amazed by young boys

01:43:02.200 --> 01:43:09.800
[Guest]: who are huge fans of some particular Hindi movie. And, you know, because they know that I'm not

01:43:09.800 --> 01:43:16.120
[Guest]: speaking Tamil very well, they assume that I speak Hindi and, you know, want to know about

01:43:16.120 --> 01:43:20.040
[Guest]: that movie or that particular singer. It's usually something that's been released in the last few

01:43:20.040 --> 01:43:25.480
[Guest]: years, so I know nothing about it. But I love discovering people's passions in that way.

01:43:26.040 --> 01:43:32.120
[Guest]: And this is what most journalists miss, that most Indians are people of ideas.

01:43:32.120 --> 01:43:35.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting. This reminded me of something corporate, in fact, where Zomato has

01:43:35.800 --> 01:43:39.960
[Amit Varma]: started this recent thing where if a delivery boy is coming to your thing, they'll say, oh,

01:43:39.960 --> 01:43:44.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, Ahmed is fond of conversation or whatever, they'll throw in a little telling

01:43:44.440 --> 01:43:49.080
[Amit Varma]: detail. And I'm immediately getting my mic set up ready and saying, should I engage in a recorded

01:43:49.080 --> 01:43:53.480
[Amit Varma]: conversation with Ahmed? But, you know, and this also goes back to, you know, what Stephen Covey

01:43:53.480 --> 01:43:59.000
[Amit Varma]: once famously said about how we listen to respond and not to understand. And you would think that

01:43:59.000 --> 01:44:03.960
[Amit Varma]: this would be such a simple thing that, you know, that we listen more, but listening is something

01:44:03.960 --> 01:44:09.240
[Amit Varma]: that we're just so horrendously bad at. And I don't know if it's something to do with a certain

01:44:09.240 --> 01:44:15.960
[Amit Varma]: kind of insecurity that is also greater and perhaps Indians and in other places that we

01:44:15.960 --> 01:44:21.000
[Amit Varma]: we're always so, you know, in need of that validation and showing that we are smarter

01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:26.680
[Amit Varma]: than the other person. And we know more that we simply don't listen enough. And that's also

01:44:26.680 --> 01:44:32.760
[Amit Varma]: something that, you know, I kind of find quite evocative. Let's take another commercial break

01:44:32.760 --> 01:44:37.240
[Amit Varma]: then. And after that, when we come back, we shall finally, finally, dear listener, finally,

