[Amit Varma]: document that in real time. And it was so fascinating to kind of binge through it. And,

01:46:30.120 --> 01:46:35.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, listen to the episodes, because one can see your sort of understanding also evolve

01:46:35.800 --> 01:46:40.120
[Amit Varma]: and the kind of questions that you ask. And what made you think of starting it?

01:46:40.120 --> 01:46:46.360
[Guest]: So I've always loved audio as a medium, without ever having done anything in it at all.

01:46:46.920 --> 01:46:52.280
[Guest]: There was one point at which I sort of, I talked to someone about doing a podcast. And then

01:46:52.280 --> 01:46:59.960
[Guest]: I realized I had such clear ideas of what I wanted it to be and sound like and, you know,

01:46:59.960 --> 01:47:05.320
[Guest]: I didn't really, I don't think I was very receptive to suggestions. And then it just,

01:47:05.320 --> 01:47:10.760
[Guest]: you know, fell by the wayside. I listened to I mean, I don't listen to a ton of podcasts,

01:47:10.760 --> 01:47:16.600
[Guest]: but I do. I know I love it. I love it as a medium. The early days of the lockdown was so

01:47:16.600 --> 01:47:24.680
[Guest]: was so strange, right? We were all in such all of us suspended in such strange positions,

01:47:24.680 --> 01:47:31.720
[Guest]: you know, frozen and all sorts of unusual outposts that I don't know if in normal times,

01:47:31.720 --> 01:47:40.280
[Guest]: I would have I would have done it. You know, it sort of felt like we were all on little boats

01:47:40.280 --> 01:47:47.000
[Guest]: out into the sea. And it was okay to send out these mosquito messages to each other. And you

01:47:47.000 --> 01:47:56.440
[Guest]: know, someone would listen to it and would feel nice hearing another sound. I would have felt

01:47:56.440 --> 01:48:01.720
[Guest]: much more self conscious if I really felt like this was you know, if I thought of it as everybody

01:48:01.720 --> 01:48:07.320
[Guest]: in their houses or their workplaces listening to it. So what was happening in the early days is

01:48:07.320 --> 01:48:15.000
[Guest]: that we really were finding out everything about the virus so fast every day. And there was not

01:48:15.000 --> 01:48:21.320
[Guest]: just news to catch up on. There was also research that I felt that I needed to read academic

01:48:21.320 --> 01:48:26.040
[Guest]: research and understand it. And I felt like every day at the end of the day, there was something

01:48:26.040 --> 01:48:32.840
[Guest]: that I was taking away from it. And I like the feeling of maybe just saying it out to myself

01:48:32.840 --> 01:48:40.440
[Guest]: that this is what I felt that I had learned through the day. And just on a whim, I, you know,

01:48:40.440 --> 01:48:46.280
[Guest]: I thought, okay, let me just use this as an opportunity to get this started. And again,

01:48:46.280 --> 01:48:53.160
[Guest]: because I didn't think of it too much, I actually put it out because otherwise now I'm so scared of

01:48:53.160 --> 01:48:58.680
[Guest]: making any sort of commitments because my time is so scattered right now, that if someone had

01:48:58.680 --> 01:49:04.280
[Guest]: approached me and said, would you like to do 100 episode podcast around the pandemic, I would have,

01:49:04.280 --> 01:49:10.760
[Guest]: you know, I would have cried with fright and said no before I could even before they could

01:49:10.760 --> 01:49:18.040
[Guest]: have finished their question. I really like the fact that I did this entirely on my own terms.

01:49:18.040 --> 01:49:21.720
[Guest]: And that's the only way I would have done it at all. Otherwise, I really would have felt too

01:49:21.720 --> 01:49:27.400
[Guest]: scared to do it. And I don't feel you know, I should feel embarrassed by the fact that

01:49:27.400 --> 01:49:33.160
[Guest]: some of it was so wrong and figuring so many things out that are probably wrong now,

01:49:33.160 --> 01:49:37.480
[Guest]: but I don't I don't really and it is from the sort of impulse that you're describing as,

01:49:38.040 --> 01:49:44.280
[Guest]: you know, first draft of history, which is, I feel like this is that hopefully, that was an example

01:49:44.280 --> 01:49:51.800
[Guest]: of fairness that all I felt that I was going in was with a questioning mind and seeing what my

01:49:51.800 --> 01:49:58.920
[Guest]: questions were producing and then fairly reproducing that without, without making up my mind too

01:49:58.920 --> 01:50:05.240
[Guest]: strongly, you know, more strongly than what the evidence was showing, at least. I hadn't even

01:50:05.240 --> 01:50:09.480
[Guest]: thought at the time that I was going to have guests on it, because all of that would have felt

01:50:09.480 --> 01:50:16.600
[Guest]: like such a grandiose and pompous thing to do for just something that I was trying out for a few

01:50:16.600 --> 01:50:22.680
[Guest]: people who want to listen to, who might want to listen to it. But immediately, I mean, just a few

01:50:22.680 --> 01:50:27.560
[Guest]: days in, I realized that I had questions that actually someone needed to answer that, you know,

01:50:27.560 --> 01:50:33.000
[Guest]: the information wasn't really available. And this is the part that's been really amazing to me. So

01:50:33.000 --> 01:50:39.720
[Guest]: people I already know, I'm of course, thankful that they come on this. But people in government

01:50:39.720 --> 01:50:45.320
[Guest]: or people, similarly sort of experts who I haven't spoken to before, because I don't cover science or

01:50:45.320 --> 01:50:51.880
[Guest]: even health that much, them agreeing to speak to me and come on this is the truly unusual part. And I

01:50:51.880 --> 01:50:58.520
[Guest]: suppose that's what demonstrates true commitment to science, that if somebody wants to know the

01:50:58.520 --> 01:51:04.680
[Guest]: science of it, you're committed enough to go and talk to them about it. And the other thing that

01:51:04.680 --> 01:51:11.800
[Guest]: always felt intimidating to me is because I'm truly very, you know, totally the opposite of

01:51:11.800 --> 01:51:18.760
[Guest]: being tech savvy. I wouldn't have known how to do any of it, you know, but this is where

01:51:19.320 --> 01:51:24.840
[Guest]: friends just have done things for me. And that's been great. So Anand Krishnamurthy, who does the

01:51:24.840 --> 01:51:34.360
[Guest]: sound for it, is a very well known, well regarded person in audio. And it's, you know, I'm just,

01:51:35.160 --> 01:51:40.440
[Guest]: he's a friend, and I'm hugely thankful that he's just doing this for me, because he too likes

01:51:40.440 --> 01:51:46.520
[Guest]: podcasts, and, you know, is interested in this, and of course, is doing it to help me out. So

01:51:47.160 --> 01:51:52.360
[Guest]: because of him, I even, I even knew that, okay, then now I have a sound file, then I have to put

01:51:52.360 --> 01:51:58.440
[Guest]: it out somewhere. Then another friend did the RSS feed part for me, which I truly know nothing about

01:51:58.440 --> 01:52:03.880
[Guest]: even now, he did it. Another friend did the artwork for free, because at some point, someone

01:52:03.880 --> 01:52:09.560
[Guest]: said, put it on Apple podcast. Oh, God, how do I do that? And then Apple podcast said original artwork.

01:52:09.560 --> 01:52:14.040
[Guest]: And then me, like a complete dimwit, instead of just throwing together something on Canva,

01:52:14.040 --> 01:52:19.640
[Guest]: I was like, oh, that means someone has to create original artwork for me. So I went to an actual

01:52:19.640 --> 01:52:25.400
[Guest]: artist friend, Satyak Gade, who's a wonderful illustrator, and he very kindly, you know,

01:52:25.400 --> 01:52:32.840
[Guest]: came up with actual original artwork, which truly seems excessive for an endeavour of this size.

01:52:32.840 --> 01:52:39.640
[Guest]: But so yeah, it's still it's, it's, I enjoy it very much. And, you know, it's an indulgence. It's

01:52:39.640 --> 01:52:45.960
[Guest]: a very small thing. It has, you know, very few, very small numbers, very few listeners. So I know

01:52:45.960 --> 01:52:52.760
[Guest]: I'm doing this for myself, and because I enjoy it, but yeah, I kept thinking, was there going to be

01:52:52.760 --> 01:52:57.720
[Guest]: a time when I would have to start winding it down now that I've reached 100 episodes? Should I just

01:52:57.720 --> 01:53:03.400
[Guest]: sort of call it off? But it's, I still enjoy it very much. So I'm going to continue doing it.

01:53:04.280 --> 01:53:07.960
[Amit Varma]: No, no, it's, it's lovely. And this whole story of this podcast is so incredibly

01:53:07.960 --> 01:53:11.720
[Amit Varma]: inspiring. And a shout out to Anant Krishnamurthy, old friend of mine, and someone like you rightly

01:53:11.720 --> 01:53:17.320
[Amit Varma]: said, he's a he's a big name in these circles in Chennai. So for him to do a podcast is just

01:53:17.320 --> 01:53:22.040
[Amit Varma]: shows, you know, his passion and his kindness as well. Remarkable chap. And I love the artwork,

01:53:22.040 --> 01:53:26.200
[Amit Varma]: by the way. And you know, why I said I find it inspiring. And you know, I'm not being overly

01:53:26.200 --> 01:53:30.840
[Amit Varma]: kind here is that, you know, when I spoke to you, when we were sort of laying out the logistics for

01:53:30.840 --> 01:53:34.840
[Amit Varma]: this particular recording, and I was so surprised to hear that you don't have a mic and all of that,

01:53:34.840 --> 01:53:39.160
[Amit Varma]: that you do it on your phone and the load, the kind of lo-fi way you've been doing it. And people

01:53:39.160 --> 01:53:43.080
[Amit Varma]: keep asking me about advice on how to start podcasts. And there are two or three that have

01:53:43.080 --> 01:53:48.520
[Amit Varma]: kind of helped bring into being. And I'm in fact, toying with the idea of teaching a course on

01:53:48.520 --> 01:53:53.480
[Amit Varma]: starting a podcast. And what I would, you know, say to everyone who is listening is that listen,

01:53:53.480 --> 01:53:57.960
[Amit Varma]: you do not need anything. Do not overthink it, just jump into it. You know, if there's something

01:53:57.960 --> 01:54:03.400
[Amit Varma]: that you think you'll enjoy doing, just kind of, you know, jump into it. Don't overthink what is

01:54:03.400 --> 01:54:09.640
[Amit Varma]: the mic I need? And how will I edit it? And, you know, and should it be 10 minutes or 12 minutes

01:54:09.640 --> 01:54:14.600
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And I think people just need to kind of jump into stuff and let it find its

01:54:14.600 --> 01:54:20.760
[Amit Varma]: own momentum. And congratulations on 100 episodes and the Emergent Ventures Prize. It's all,

01:54:20.760 --> 01:54:26.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, so incredibly inspiring. Let's now talk a little bit about sort of the subject matter. And

01:54:26.280 --> 01:54:31.480
[Amit Varma]: like you said, when you started, and we were really in what one could call the fog of pandemic,

01:54:31.480 --> 01:54:36.440
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, everybody's trying to figure it out. And you are sort of, in a sense, documenting

01:54:36.440 --> 01:54:42.120
[Amit Varma]: your own intellectual journey through your podcast of figuring out what's going on. So,

01:54:42.120 --> 01:54:48.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, where did that quest begin? Like, did you look at the way it was being reported and said,

01:54:48.200 --> 01:54:53.000
[Amit Varma]: okay, these are the lacunae and these are the areas where I wish somebody was, you know,

01:54:53.000 --> 01:54:58.040
[Amit Varma]: looking at XYZ? And hey, I'm going to do that. What's the available data at that time? How do

01:54:58.040 --> 01:55:03.560
[Amit Varma]: you begin to make sense of it? There are so many models and projections also, you know, going

01:55:03.560 --> 01:55:07.800
[Amit Varma]: around, where does one begin? What was your thinking in those early days when you kind of got

01:55:07.800 --> 01:55:16.520
[Guest]: into it? So I think there were two stages to this. The first was the absolute, you know, early days

01:55:16.520 --> 01:55:23.400
[Guest]: when I felt that there was very little sort of big picture reporting happening from India. I was

01:55:23.400 --> 01:55:31.080
[Guest]: seeing a lot of this in the US and the UK. But I didn't feel like there was much reporting happening

01:55:31.080 --> 01:55:38.680
[Guest]: that yet about the nature of the virus, how it spreads, what we know about aerosols, any of that

01:55:38.680 --> 01:55:43.000
[Guest]: right then, because it was more about, you know, what the government's going to do, are we going

01:55:43.000 --> 01:55:48.200
[Guest]: to have a lockdown, that sort of stuff in the early days. So I felt like I was able to at least

01:55:48.200 --> 01:55:56.680
[Guest]: maybe not say things anew, but synthesize things anew. There was that sort of new endeavor to do

01:55:56.680 --> 01:56:01.880
[Guest]: in that. But then the other thing that ended up happening very quickly, and you know, I know this

01:56:01.880 --> 01:56:07.640
[Guest]: is a theme that I've talked about before as well, which is that I struggle a lot and think a lot

01:56:07.640 --> 01:56:17.640
[Guest]: about polarization. And it became very evident to me very quickly that this had once again become

01:56:17.640 --> 01:56:24.680
[Guest]: a left-right thing. And it really bothered me deeply, because it became very clear that for

01:56:24.680 --> 01:56:30.120
[Guest]: people on the left, it was now becoming necessary to say that the Modi government was mishandling

01:56:30.120 --> 01:56:36.200
[Guest]: everything, that its testing strategy was not just conservative, but was also conservative

01:56:36.200 --> 01:56:42.680
[Guest]: to try to show low numbers, that there was, you know, pseudoscience running amok, that

01:56:44.040 --> 01:56:48.120
[Guest]: there were soon going to be millions of deaths that was happening. And then on the other side,

01:56:49.720 --> 01:56:55.240
[Guest]: immediately that the lockdown was an enormous success, the lockdown was going to make sure

01:56:55.240 --> 01:57:00.600
[Guest]: that we were not going to have any more cases. You know, there's the very memorable graph by

01:57:00.600 --> 01:57:06.200
[Guest]: DK Pal, the government's COVID task force, which showed, I think this was in early April,

01:57:06.200 --> 01:57:13.160
[Guest]: and it showed a curve of cases rising, and then inexplicably on May 16, hitting zero.

01:57:13.800 --> 01:57:20.920
[Guest]: I mean, it just nosedived into an axis in a way that you rarely see any graph anywhere doing.

01:57:21.480 --> 01:57:28.040
[Guest]: So there was that sort of optimistic graph storytelling as well. And

01:57:28.040 --> 01:57:32.280
[Guest]: it was incredibly frustrating to me that this was again, becoming a left right thing.

01:57:32.280 --> 01:57:37.720
[Guest]: And I wanted to, I wanted to talk about, I'm not a science journalist, and I knew that there was

01:57:37.720 --> 01:57:43.800
[Guest]: very little of the science that I was going to say anything meaningful about, I was listening

01:57:43.800 --> 01:57:48.920
[Guest]: and reading about it. I'm interested, even though I'm not a good science communicator,

01:57:48.920 --> 01:57:55.960
[Guest]: but I knew I wanted to talk about the policy parts of it. And in a way that could get through

01:57:55.960 --> 01:58:03.560
[Guest]: this sort of frustrating left right situation that was already developing. So around mortality,

01:58:03.560 --> 01:58:08.280
[Guest]: for example, you know, at the point at which numbers became large enough to start sort of

01:58:08.280 --> 01:58:13.400
[Guest]: comparing with the rest of the world, it became clear that there was a larger story to tell

01:58:13.400 --> 01:58:20.760
[Guest]: about mortality, which included the fact that India does underreport most deaths from most

01:58:20.760 --> 01:58:28.200
[Guest]: diseases, while simultaneously reconciling with the fact that there did appear to be

01:58:29.320 --> 01:58:34.040
[Guest]: lower COVID mortality in India than in some Western countries for reasons that needed to

01:58:34.040 --> 01:58:41.960
[Guest]: be understood and analyzed. So I do remember feeling at that point that I absolutely had not

01:58:41.960 --> 01:58:47.320
[Guest]: seen. And this is where we talk about, you know, the lack of imagination and how to tell stories,

01:58:47.320 --> 01:58:52.280
[Guest]: right? You know, no one is going to pitch or get approval for an op-ed that says I'm going to,

01:58:52.280 --> 01:58:58.600
[Guest]: I'm going to write an op-ed considering all the aspects of the mortality issue. News reporters

01:58:58.600 --> 01:59:07.000
[Guest]: never go in for a 360 thing anyway, either. So this became a sort of way to be able to talk about

01:59:07.000 --> 01:59:12.280
[Guest]: all of the different things that were happening on mortality. So yes, there were a couple of

01:59:12.280 --> 01:59:17.960
[Guest]: very specific things that I felt that I was not hearing, or at least that I, you know,

01:59:18.520 --> 01:59:23.160
[Guest]: wanted to synthesize and be able to say. And you know, the polarization, the politics is

01:59:23.160 --> 01:59:28.600
[Amit Varma]: something that you mentioned in, you know, a bunch of episodes, episode 22 and 93 are about

01:59:28.600 --> 01:59:33.560
[Amit Varma]: sort of the left-right binaries. You know, in episode 65, you handled, you know, another

01:59:33.560 --> 01:59:38.280
[Amit Varma]: political issue, the discussion around hydroxychloroquine. You spoke about the missing

01:59:38.280 --> 01:59:43.560
[Amit Varma]: deaths in episode 80, and whether, you know, the understating of deaths could have sort of a

01:59:43.560 --> 01:59:49.160
[Amit Varma]: political impetus. And is it then from readers say, I mean, I know, like, thankfully, you mentioned

01:59:49.160 --> 01:59:54.120
[Amit Varma]: that you're not on social media all the time and all of that. But is there also then a sense of

01:59:54.120 --> 01:59:59.160
[Amit Varma]: frustration among some people that you're not sort of that you're going into a level of nuance

01:59:59.160 --> 02:00:05.320
[Amit Varma]: that doesn't really fit any of the easy narratives? You are, you know, kind of carving your own path

02:00:05.320 --> 02:00:11.240
[Amit Varma]: through it. Was it that sense also kind of happening? So, I get that from my regular

02:00:11.240 --> 02:00:19.160
[Guest]: journalism a lot. I get that sort of response very often. So, for example, you know, I got pushed back

02:00:19.160 --> 02:00:26.440
[Guest]: after, in the very early days, pre-lockdown as well, I wrote for Mint about death statistics

02:00:26.440 --> 02:00:32.360
[Guest]: in general in India. So that, you know, the feeling of, let's go into this pandemic

02:00:32.360 --> 02:00:38.280
[Guest]: with an understanding of how deaths get reported in India and where things might fall short.

02:00:38.280 --> 02:00:42.760
[Guest]: And, you know, it was immediately, I mean, it's not uniform always, but there was some

02:00:42.760 --> 02:00:47.720
[Guest]: criticism of that, okay, here you're already building a narrative that we're undercounting

02:00:47.720 --> 02:00:56.680
[Guest]: deaths. So, I get that from my regular news reporting quite a bit. And this is where,

02:00:56.680 --> 02:01:03.080
[Guest]: you know, as I said, I don't have big numbers at all on the podcast. And so, what I feel is,

02:01:03.880 --> 02:01:12.280
[Guest]: you know, the podcast audience is, in some ways, a new sort of pandemic community has built a little

02:01:12.280 --> 02:01:18.040
[Guest]: bit on social media as well. And many of them are scientists who are not epidemiologists,

02:01:18.040 --> 02:01:24.280
[Guest]: but who are sort of more amateur enthusiasts. And that's a sweet spot for me because

02:01:24.280 --> 02:01:30.600
[Guest]: I'm not going to make points of great interest to experts at all in any way. But people who want

02:01:30.600 --> 02:01:37.400
[Guest]: slightly research-backed and considered arguments that look at a number of points of view,

02:01:37.400 --> 02:01:43.240
[Guest]: this is of interest to them. So, no, what I actually get is, I get, you know,

02:01:43.960 --> 02:01:52.360
[Guest]: appreciation for the nuance on the podcast, because that is a community that is very different from my

02:01:52.360 --> 02:01:58.440
[Amit Varma]: news-reading community. Yeah, and that's, in fact, you know, even though you do T20s and I do test

02:01:58.440 --> 02:02:03.160
[Amit Varma]: matches, I can say that I've kind of noticed the same difference with my podcast listeners,

02:02:03.160 --> 02:02:09.240
[Amit Varma]: that I'll never get those kind of harsh, real, personal, almost toxic responses that one

02:02:09.240 --> 02:02:12.680
[Amit Varma]: otherwise might get in social media, where people are just reading the headline of your piece and

02:02:12.680 --> 02:02:19.160
[Amit Varma]: responding to that at the level of engagement and respect is much deeper, and in your case,

02:02:19.160 --> 02:02:24.680
[Amit Varma]: obviously earned. One of the things that sort of interested me is that, you know, while charting

02:02:24.680 --> 02:02:29.240
[Amit Varma]: the journey of your podcast, one of the beautiful things that you did was you decided that you'll

02:02:29.240 --> 02:02:35.000
[Amit Varma]: ask one question in every episode. So, episode seven, why aren't we all wearing masks? Episode

02:02:35.000 --> 02:02:38.680
[Amit Varma]: eight, there is, you know, how are hospitals treating the virus when we don't even know the

02:02:38.680 --> 02:02:44.120
[Amit Varma]: cure? What will life after the lockdown look like? Should we trust the models? And so on and so

02:02:44.120 --> 02:02:50.760
[Amit Varma]: forth. And it was interesting for me to see those questions evolve from sort of specific questions

02:02:50.760 --> 02:02:56.920
[Amit Varma]: like around masks or around lockdowns and go to those deeper, broader questions as the series

02:02:56.920 --> 02:03:03.400
[Amit Varma]: progressed. For example, in episode 20 and 21, you, you know, worried about how through this

02:03:03.400 --> 02:03:08.920
[Amit Varma]: COVID crisis, our rights and our privacies and all of all of those are sort of being eroded and

02:03:08.920 --> 02:03:13.400
[Amit Varma]: the danger of greater authoritarianism and the power of the state expanding. Tell me a little

02:03:13.400 --> 02:03:19.720
[Amit Varma]: bit about sort of your thinking on that. And do you feel that those worries are kind of borne out?

02:03:19.720 --> 02:03:24.760
[Amit Varma]: What do we need to watch out for? What are the concrete signs that, you know, citizens are being

02:03:24.760 --> 02:03:30.440
[Amit Varma]: even more disempowered than they already were? Right. So the question part of it, I thought I

02:03:30.440 --> 02:03:36.520
[Guest]: was going, you know, I did feel like I was going into it with a questioning mind. And I did feel

02:03:36.520 --> 02:03:41.320
[Guest]: like I was going and trying to answer the question each time. As it went on, I started worrying about

02:03:41.320 --> 02:03:45.960
[Guest]: whether this was going to become like an artifact that I was hanging on to. But it hasn't. I do,

02:03:45.960 --> 02:03:51.640
[Guest]: I do feel that I do have these questions and that I am in pursuit of some sort of answer

02:03:53.000 --> 02:03:58.680
[Guest]: to them in each of these. I think, you know, there was a phase in the pandemic when we all wondered

02:03:59.400 --> 02:04:05.000
[Guest]: how different things were going to be after this was all over. And, you know, I think we all went

02:04:05.000 --> 02:04:11.400
[Guest]: through a phase of great hope, a feeling that there was going to be a sort of pan-human solidarity.

02:04:11.960 --> 02:04:18.040
[Guest]: Then, you know, there were times when that evaporated and we worried if we were going to

02:04:18.040 --> 02:04:24.040
[Guest]: get into a, you know, huge surveillance when Aarogya Setu started. That was, you know,

02:04:24.040 --> 02:04:31.560
[Guest]: a real concern then. So all of those great hopes for great change, I think, have gone through their

02:04:31.560 --> 02:04:39.400
[Guest]: own waves and dissipated a little. And I think what we're increasingly left with is that we're

02:04:39.400 --> 02:04:46.600
[Guest]: going to be left with a world not dissimilar from what was there before, with some things having been

02:04:47.240 --> 02:04:53.480
[Guest]: made worse for the most vulnerable people. So, you know, what we're seeing is, for example,

02:04:53.480 --> 02:04:59.160
[Guest]: you know, jobs beginning to return. But everywhere people are seeing that working seniors are

02:04:59.160 --> 02:05:06.440
[Guest]: deeply struggling. Anyone with very little elbow room is struggling deeply. So I don't think the

02:05:06.440 --> 02:05:12.360
[Guest]: sort of dystopian vision that we were also once having was that, you know, all of the worst in

02:05:12.360 --> 02:05:18.440
[Guest]: people was coming out, the sort of awful stigma that began at one point. And, you know, it seemed

02:05:18.440 --> 02:05:24.440
[Guest]: like we were going to build the ghettos of our nightmares were now going to start coming up.

02:05:24.440 --> 02:05:29.880
[Guest]: I think that's all also giving way to pragmatism. And that's not how things are going to be like

02:05:29.880 --> 02:05:36.280
[Guest]: as well. But I don't know, I'm sure that there are going to be traumas from this period that

02:05:36.280 --> 02:05:42.920
[Guest]: are not going to go away easily. So, for example, you know, I know it's extremely obvious,

02:05:42.920 --> 02:05:47.720
[Guest]: but having recently spoken to someone about it, that there have been one million deaths worldwide.

02:05:47.720 --> 02:05:55.240
[Guest]: So that is one million families, for the most part across the world, who were not able to get

02:05:55.960 --> 02:06:06.360
[Guest]: a final goodbye. That is an enormous sort of shared drama that a truly large number of people

02:06:06.360 --> 02:06:13.160
[Guest]: have had to go through. The sort of terrifying fears of the lockdown, which are now, you know,

02:06:13.160 --> 02:06:17.000
[Guest]: now they're a bit of a distant memory. I don't go out that much as well. But

02:06:17.000 --> 02:06:22.440
[Guest]: sometimes it's really something to remember, you know, that it was not allowed, you were not

02:06:22.440 --> 02:06:30.920
[Guest]: allowed to leave home. And what that meant like for people for anyone for whom home was not happy.

02:06:31.560 --> 02:06:37.320
[Guest]: Again, I know someone firsthand who lived an absolute nightmare through those days. And

02:06:38.520 --> 02:06:45.320
[Guest]: that, again, is a huge cohort of people for whom that trauma of living in, you know,

02:06:45.320 --> 02:06:51.880
[Guest]: imprisonment for those days is not going away. I don't think that, you know, either our worst

02:06:51.880 --> 02:06:58.920
[Guest]: fears or our best hopes about the post-COVID world are going to come true. But there are going to be

02:07:00.280 --> 02:07:09.480
[Guest]: scars and cleavages and maybe even little sort of seedlings of better things that will slowly

02:07:09.480 --> 02:07:17.720
[Guest]: make themselves apparent, not in any of the terribly obvious ways that we had once wondered

02:07:17.720 --> 02:07:22.920
[Guest]: about. But it's going to be that that part's going to be interesting to see how that changes.

02:07:23.880 --> 02:07:28.600
[Guest]: You know, for example, one of the things that happened was a big change in the number of hours

02:07:28.600 --> 02:07:35.560
[Guest]: of unpaid housework that men began to do. And that gap has narrowed significantly now.

02:07:35.560 --> 02:07:41.960
[Guest]: But if that gap, you know, still that space remains, then that is still a fundamental

02:07:41.960 --> 02:07:47.560
[Guest]: shift in society and what that means for the next 30 years. Because if that slight increment,

02:07:47.560 --> 02:07:53.080
[Guest]: if we don't go back to that little bit of the old normal, that's still that's still something.

02:07:53.080 --> 02:07:59.320
[Guest]: So, yeah, it's I don't think that there's going to be, you know, dramatic changes from what

02:07:59.320 --> 02:08:08.680
[Guest]: happened. But, you know, a series of small and maybe even unknowable, as of now, changes.

02:08:08.680 --> 02:08:13.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, just thinking aloud, it strikes me that what happened to all of us very suddenly,

02:08:13.080 --> 02:08:18.680
[Amit Varma]: when all of this happened was that we were sort of, you know, living with complacence in

02:08:18.680 --> 02:08:23.640
[Amit Varma]: the inertia of the cocoon of that normality, which we had built around ourselves. And by

02:08:23.640 --> 02:08:30.520
[Amit Varma]: breaking us out of that, we were all forced to examine deeper truths of different kinds.

02:08:30.520 --> 02:08:33.880
[Amit Varma]: Maybe it could be that you cannot stand the person you're living with, maybe it could be

02:08:33.880 --> 02:08:37.720
[Amit Varma]: that you discover new things about them and fall in love all over again, or whatever,

02:08:37.720 --> 02:08:42.840
[Amit Varma]: in various different ways, we kind of broke out of, you know, the different cocoons we

02:08:42.840 --> 02:08:47.080
[Amit Varma]: might have created, which were perhaps set in our everyday routines and all of that.

02:08:47.080 --> 02:08:51.080
[Amit Varma]: The other thing I want to ask you about, and I guess you'd, I think you'd have insight on

02:08:51.080 --> 02:08:54.920
[Amit Varma]: that in a different context also, and not just COVID, is when you were talking about,

02:08:54.920 --> 02:08:59.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, fears of the surveillance of the state and all of that. And it struck me that

02:09:00.600 --> 02:09:07.320
[Amit Varma]: the one thing that saves us from even greater oppression by the state is the incompetence of

02:09:07.320 --> 02:09:12.040
[Amit Varma]: the state. Because the state typically just doesn't have state capacity, there isn't much

02:09:13.000 --> 02:09:17.480
[Amit Varma]: depth and nuance to what they do, the tools with which they oppress are blunt tools.

02:09:17.480 --> 02:09:22.840
[Amit Varma]: And many of these high tech tools of surveillance and even using Aaragya Setu in meaningfully

02:09:22.840 --> 02:09:29.160
[Amit Varma]: oppressive ways is possibly beyond the state. Now, in a larger context, is that true? Because

02:09:29.160 --> 02:09:33.640
[Amit Varma]: of course, you have to, you know, I'm sure you've thought very deeply about your relationship with

02:09:33.640 --> 02:09:39.480
[Amit Varma]: the state, because in a lot of cases, you're depending on data from the state. And sometimes

02:09:39.480 --> 02:09:45.160
[Amit Varma]: you've pointed out before you realize that it's not that the bad data is necessarily malign,

02:09:45.160 --> 02:09:48.920
[Amit Varma]: it is just incompetent. And what are your sort of thoughts on this?

02:09:49.800 --> 02:09:53.960
[Guest]: Yeah, I find myself saying this a lot to people a lot, which is that

02:09:55.560 --> 02:10:00.680
[Guest]: so much of what is imagined to be malice is actually incompetence. And I, you know,

02:10:00.680 --> 02:10:07.320
[Guest]: this is a recurring theme through reporting and through reporting on data as well. And,

02:10:07.320 --> 02:10:12.520
[Guest]: you know, assuming malafide is something that bothers me when people are talking about

02:10:12.520 --> 02:10:16.840
[Guest]: people that they are ideologically opposed to, again, this is something that I felt that

02:10:17.960 --> 02:10:22.440
[Guest]: marked some of the criticism of the government's handling of COVID as well, which is

02:10:23.320 --> 02:10:27.320
[Guest]: frequently assuming malafide intentions, when I don't think it called for that,

02:10:27.960 --> 02:10:36.120
[Guest]: you know, assuming suppression of numbers, when the sheer capacity to count properly,

02:10:36.120 --> 02:10:43.080
[Guest]: you know, did not exist, assuming that the government was trying was, you know, keep reducing

02:10:43.080 --> 02:10:48.440
[Guest]: tests so that it wouldn't discover more cases when I feel they just did not have the capacity

02:10:48.440 --> 02:10:54.440
[Guest]: to conduct more tests then. And similarly, about deaths as well, when you see that this is

02:10:54.440 --> 02:11:00.120
[Guest]: something that they fail, you know, they fail at with all diseases, it isn't a new decision to

02:11:00.120 --> 02:11:10.280
[Guest]: start failing at it, when it comes to COVID. So, this is true. But I should also, you know,

02:11:11.800 --> 02:11:17.640
[Guest]: sometimes I make this such a, I make such a point of this that I don't want to sort of fall in love

02:11:17.640 --> 02:11:22.440
[Guest]: with my own point and get carried away with it as well. I do think I do this about the government

02:11:22.440 --> 02:11:30.040
[Guest]: and incompetence. And occasionally, journalists prove malice. And it's great when they do that,

02:11:30.040 --> 02:11:39.480
[Guest]: because it reminds me then that I shouldn't, I shouldn't assume that the bumbling lathiwala cop

02:11:39.480 --> 02:11:45.000
[Guest]: is the Indian state. It's not true at all. There's a sort of lovable awfulness to that.

02:11:45.000 --> 02:11:52.840
[Guest]: But that's not true. So, you know, one of the most excellent journalists of the last few years has

02:11:52.840 --> 02:11:59.400
[Guest]: been Somesh Jha of Business Standard, who has come at data journalism in a way that I don't think I

02:11:59.400 --> 02:12:04.040
[Guest]: have been able to do for the most part. And that is a very valuable new direction to be going,

02:12:04.040 --> 02:12:09.960
[Guest]: which is to get into the making of the sausage and the corruption of the sausage makers to

02:12:09.960 --> 02:12:17.000
[Guest]: extend this too far. He is the journalist who discovered that the government was sitting on

02:12:17.000 --> 02:12:22.440
[Guest]: both employment and household consumption information data, which had been cleared by

02:12:22.440 --> 02:12:28.440
[Guest]: all committees and was statistically sound, but showed uncomfortable truths as clear,

02:12:29.160 --> 02:12:33.720
[Guest]: you know, as malafide intentions get is that showed the government in a poor light.

02:12:33.720 --> 02:12:40.040
[Guest]: And then the government too was shameless enough to deny his news reporting, you know,

02:12:40.040 --> 02:12:47.000
[Guest]: have surrogates criticize it and him, and then release exactly those numbers the day they came

02:12:47.000 --> 02:12:54.280
[Guest]: back to power. I mean, that was one of the most brazen and shocking things to have happened when

02:12:54.280 --> 02:13:00.760
[Guest]: it comes to data. You know, I too was willing to accept that, that there were some reasons that

02:13:00.760 --> 02:13:05.400
[Guest]: there was some fine tuning, but this sort of brazen release of it on the day they came back to

02:13:05.400 --> 02:13:12.360
[Guest]: power was truly shocking even to me. So, I think so much has done a good job of showing how much

02:13:13.080 --> 02:13:20.440
[Guest]: malice exists as well. And, you know, much as I've criticized crime reporting so far, I think

02:13:21.400 --> 02:13:29.080
[Guest]: sometimes what good crime reporters do is to show the most venal part of the Indian state,

02:13:29.080 --> 02:13:37.240
[Guest]: right? The venality of cops can be, is sort of the most distilled form of the venality of the

02:13:37.240 --> 02:13:44.520
[Guest]: Indian state sometimes. So, I like making that rather various ironic bumbling incompetence point,

02:13:44.520 --> 02:13:49.800
[Guest]: but I think people like Soumesh and a lot of crime reporters are able to show that,

02:13:50.440 --> 02:13:54.280
[Amit Varma]: that we wish it was as cute as that. Yeah. And I guess one thinking a lot,

02:13:54.280 --> 02:14:00.120
[Amit Varma]: one could even say that, you know, even if the means are incompetent, the end is for all practical

02:14:00.120 --> 02:14:04.920
[Amit Varma]: purposes malicious. I mean, what difference does it then make what the intent is if that's

02:14:04.920 --> 02:14:10.280
[Amit Varma]: kind of where we've ended up? Let's kind of talk about COVID and your sort of understanding

02:14:10.280 --> 02:14:14.520
[Amit Varma]: of it through data. So, you know, when it all broke and when you began the moving curve,

02:14:14.520 --> 02:14:20.760
[Amit Varma]: what kind of data were you looking at specifically to make sense of all of it? And then how did that

02:14:20.760 --> 02:14:25.640
[Amit Varma]: sense of what data should you look at evolve with time? How did the frame shift?

02:14:26.200 --> 02:14:31.640
[Guest]: So, I think in the early days, a lot of what I was looking at was scientific research rather than

02:14:32.200 --> 02:14:40.600
[Guest]: data. And then I think that continued for the most part. So again, when it comes to COVID and data,

02:14:40.600 --> 02:14:46.120
[Guest]: I think this was one more moment when I had to re-examine one of my favorite beliefs about the

02:14:46.120 --> 02:14:52.600
[Guest]: Indian state, which is I often get a bit annoyed by people cribbing about how little data the

02:14:52.600 --> 02:14:59.320
[Guest]: government puts out or how little data that exists, what difficult formats it is in, because I don't

02:14:59.320 --> 02:15:05.480
[Guest]: think that there's very little. I think there's quite a bit. I think it lacks in some key areas

02:15:05.480 --> 02:15:09.880
[Guest]: and might be frustrating to not have that there. There's a periodicity issue for sure, because it

02:15:09.880 --> 02:15:15.960
[Guest]: just takes so long to put things together. And sure, formats are annoying, but there are tech

02:15:15.960 --> 02:15:23.800
[Guest]: solutions for that. But when this came around, I had to accept that the amount of data that the

02:15:23.800 --> 02:15:31.640
[Guest]: government was and is until today putting out was a real shame and a real travesty. And either it's

02:15:31.640 --> 02:15:36.920
[Guest]: appalling that government systems are only able to capture that much data, or it's appalling that

02:15:36.920 --> 02:15:41.480
[Guest]: they think and have successfully until now got away with giving us that little.

02:15:41.480 --> 02:15:48.600
[Guest]: So I look not only at Western countries' data, I look at quite a few Latin American countries'

02:15:48.600 --> 02:15:54.600
[Guest]: data as well. And I've looked at South Africa at least. And for all of this, I go to their

02:15:54.600 --> 02:16:01.960
[Guest]: government websites and use Google Translate. Chile, Peru, everybody is able to put out,

02:16:01.960 --> 02:16:08.680
[Guest]: drill down to the smallest municipality, historical data for confirmed cases, deaths,

02:16:09.480 --> 02:16:14.920
[Guest]: in some cases hospitalizations. Some countries put out asymptomatic, symptomatic. Some of them

02:16:14.920 --> 02:16:21.880
[Guest]: put out probable cases. All of this in downloadable form. I have not come across a single country that

02:16:21.880 --> 02:16:28.440
[Guest]: officially puts out as little data as the Indian government does. And it's just shameful that we've

02:16:28.440 --> 02:16:34.120
[Guest]: allowed them to get away with this, to the point that every international media organization and

02:16:34.120 --> 02:16:41.720
[Guest]: researcher uses a crowdsourced website. All of us use covid19india.org, which is an amazing

02:16:41.720 --> 02:16:49.000
[Guest]: resource put together by people seeking no credit and money, who collate official data from

02:16:49.000 --> 02:16:55.800
[Guest]: government handles. And all of us are just using it and considering it acceptable to be using it

02:16:55.800 --> 02:17:04.760
[Guest]: from a.org website, when this is absolutely the core job of a government. And I have not seen any

02:17:04.760 --> 02:17:10.680
[Guest]: country that does such a poor job. I have not seen a single Latin American country or any of the

02:17:11.400 --> 02:17:17.240
[Guest]: few African countries that I've seen do such a poor job of putting out data in the pandemic. So,

02:17:17.240 --> 02:17:25.880
[Guest]: you know, reporting on data was limited in the early days. Now we have, we have through covid19india.org

02:17:25.880 --> 02:17:33.240
[Guest]: and through other, some sort of research efforts based in India as well, you know, more data to

02:17:33.240 --> 02:17:39.560
[Guest]: write about. But even now, the most interesting insights to me continue to come from scientific

02:17:39.560 --> 02:17:48.680
[Guest]: research. Understanding just how the virus spreads, among whom and why, remains the key thing to try

02:17:48.680 --> 02:17:53.640
[Guest]: and understand for people trying to live their lives going forward. And I hope what we're going

02:17:53.640 --> 02:17:57.960
[Guest]: to have now, we've had one good paper coming out of India so far, I hope what we're going to have

02:17:57.960 --> 02:18:04.440
[Guest]: more of now is good Indian scientific, you know, and by good I mean not published in ICMR's own

02:18:04.440 --> 02:18:11.640
[Guest]: ICMR's own in-house journal, but in sort of peer-reviewed reputed journals that explain

02:18:11.640 --> 02:18:16.360
[Amit Varma]: transmission patterns in India. And from what you're saying, you know, would it be correct also

02:18:16.360 --> 02:18:22.840
[Amit Varma]: to say that Indians fundamentally have a shallow understanding of what it means to be a democracy,

02:18:22.840 --> 02:18:27.800
[Amit Varma]: that we often think of democracy as, oh, there are elections and we vote one of the competing

02:18:27.800 --> 02:18:33.880
[Amit Varma]: mafias into power, but actually democracy should also include the state being accountable to the

02:18:33.880 --> 02:18:38.280
[Amit Varma]: citizens and empowering them with information, which is why data becomes so important. It's

02:18:38.280 --> 02:18:42.920
[Amit Varma]: not an aside that, oh, other states do this particular thing well and we don't. This should

02:18:42.920 --> 02:18:47.960
[Amit Varma]: actually be essential to what the state does and, you know, in a sense, part of the justification

02:18:47.960 --> 02:18:53.560
[Guest]: for its existence. Would you agree with that? Yeah, I do agree with that, though I don't fully

02:18:53.560 --> 02:18:59.960
[Guest]: agree with the shallow democracy part of it. I mean, it is, it's sort of like a puddle that's

02:18:59.960 --> 02:19:05.960
[Guest]: shallow in parts and deep in others. This part is certainly shallow in the expectation that

02:19:05.960 --> 02:19:10.040
[Guest]: government should give you this information. And you see it from just the, you know,

02:19:10.600 --> 02:19:15.560
[Guest]: the attitude that anyone assumes in a government office while demanding information that the

02:19:15.560 --> 02:19:20.360
[Guest]: office requires in law to give you. But it's still a sort of, you know, please can I have

02:19:20.360 --> 02:19:27.160
[Guest]: this posture that everybody is sort of obliged to take up? And yes, I've had this in a couple

02:19:27.160 --> 02:19:33.880
[Guest]: of interactions with government officials myself. At one point, some weeks ago, I,

02:19:35.720 --> 02:19:39.720
[Guest]: at the point when Telangana was having a pretty bad time with its numbers,

02:19:39.720 --> 02:19:48.120
[Guest]: Casey, our son, did a ask me anything sort of thing on Twitter. So I asked why Telangana bulletin had

02:19:48.120 --> 02:19:54.520
[Guest]: so much less information than other states did, which was an issue and still is. And he replied

02:19:54.520 --> 02:20:01.320
[Guest]: saying, no, it's all in there. And it wasn't. And I said, you know, the reason I'm asking you is

02:20:01.320 --> 02:20:06.760
[Guest]: because it's not in there. And he didn't get back to me further. Then one of the, you know,

02:20:06.760 --> 02:20:12.440
[Guest]: municipal corporations that's been doing a relatively good job with data is Mumbai. And

02:20:14.360 --> 02:20:22.360
[Guest]: there's a very impressive IAS officer who's leading the data side of things as well. So

02:20:22.360 --> 02:20:27.800
[Guest]: recently on Twitter, I pointed out to her that while they had this dashboard that was doing a

02:20:27.800 --> 02:20:34.760
[Guest]: very good job, like most government websites, it was updated afresh every day with no archive,

02:20:34.760 --> 02:20:40.440
[Guest]: like, you know, one of those sort of Cinderella things where everything disappears at midnight

02:20:40.440 --> 02:20:47.000
[Guest]: every day, which is so deeply frustrating to me to not be able to say, you know, make a chart for

02:20:47.000 --> 02:20:53.080
[Guest]: myself looking at trends over time. And she said, well, we don't want to overburden people with

02:20:53.080 --> 02:20:57.400
[Guest]: information. Anyone who wants more can always get in touch with us. And I just thought, I mean,

02:20:57.400 --> 02:21:02.440
[Guest]: how hard would it be just to just have a dropdown where you give the option of having historical

02:21:02.440 --> 02:21:07.320
[Guest]: data there. But, you know, that was, I mean, although she seems really great at her job and

02:21:07.320 --> 02:21:12.680
[Guest]: has done a lot, there was that attitude of, you know, don't ask us for excessive amounts of

02:21:12.680 --> 02:21:18.040
[Guest]: information. So this was something that every, you know, municipality in Colombia, for example,

02:21:18.040 --> 02:21:22.760
[Guest]: is putting out. There's another official in Bangalore as well, who's really very good on

02:21:22.760 --> 02:21:29.480
[Guest]: data and very good at sharing as well. But one of the things that India has been doing,

02:21:29.480 --> 02:21:35.800
[Guest]: that many Indian states are doing, which is quite unusual, is doing much more rapid antigen tests

02:21:35.800 --> 02:21:41.480
[Guest]: than the sort of gold standard RT-PCR test. There's ways to argue it either way. It's a

02:21:41.480 --> 02:21:47.640
[Guest]: discussion to be had. And one of the things that, you know, would be very valuable to have is the

02:21:47.640 --> 02:21:53.960
[Guest]: relative positivity rates for antigen tests versus RT-PCR. And no state is putting out that

02:21:53.960 --> 02:21:59.160
[Guest]: information. Mumbai puts it out in a graph. And when I asked for it in Excel form, I was told,

02:21:59.160 --> 02:22:03.560
[Guest]: you know, that's an excessive amount of information to ask for. And similarly, the Bangalore person

02:22:03.560 --> 02:22:10.360
[Guest]: was not happy to be asked about it, said Delhi doesn't put it out. How many columns can we put

02:22:10.360 --> 02:22:17.240
[Guest]: in every page? So, yeah, there is that information, that attitude even among the relatively, the ones

02:22:17.240 --> 02:22:21.400
[Guest]: who are putting out much more data than you're used to getting from and are much more responsive

02:22:21.400 --> 02:22:29.000
[Guest]: than you're used to government officials of, you know, don't push this so far. Don't ask for like

02:22:29.000 --> 02:22:36.360
[Guest]: Excel sheets, you know, it's pretty good how far we're getting. So definitely that attitude of

02:22:36.360 --> 02:22:40.520
[Guest]: anything more than sort of the headline number is a favor we're doing for you.

02:22:40.520 --> 02:22:44.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Well, you know, one of the things I sort of noticed through the series is that it is,

02:22:44.600 --> 02:22:49.240
[Amit Varma]: of course, not just about COVID. It is about a lot else. And a lot of that comes from,

02:22:49.240 --> 02:22:54.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, prior work you must have done. For example, in episode three, you know, there is

02:22:54.040 --> 02:22:59.320
[Amit Varma]: sort of what was certainly a new insight for me where you say, quote, poor people report more

02:22:59.320 --> 02:23:05.080
[Amit Varma]: illness, but less hospitalization. We'll stop quote. And again, that's something that, you know,

02:23:05.080 --> 02:23:09.160
[Amit Varma]: was an important insight. And I had to kind of sit down and process it and all of that.

02:23:09.160 --> 02:23:14.360
[Amit Varma]: And equally, you've touched on many sort of larger issues, like what would COVID mean for India's

02:23:14.360 --> 02:23:21.240
[Amit Varma]: women in episode 47, Dalits in episode 46, children in episode 70. In fact, you had multiple episodes

02:23:21.240 --> 02:23:27.480
[Amit Varma]: where you've looked at the impact on parents and children. Now, you know, one thing that is often

02:23:27.480 --> 02:23:32.120
[Amit Varma]: said, you know, Orville has spoken about the link between writing and thinking and one saw that is

02:23:32.120 --> 02:23:38.280
[Amit Varma]: often given is that just forcing yourself to write clearly forces you to think more clearly. And one

02:23:38.280 --> 02:23:42.680
[Amit Varma]: of the things that sort of struck me was that by the end of the series, and of course, it hasn't

02:23:42.680 --> 02:23:49.720
[Amit Varma]: ended, but you know, at episode 99, where we are and just touching 100, what struck me was that

02:23:49.720 --> 02:23:55.720
[Amit Varma]: you've gone in there asking questions as a generalist, which all journalists are in a sense,

02:23:55.720 --> 02:24:02.280
[Amit Varma]: they are generalists. But have you then by asking questions repeatedly, repeatedly, repeatedly

02:24:02.280 --> 02:24:06.920
[Amit Varma]: looking at the data, looking at the research, in a manner of speaking, transformed yourself into an

02:24:06.920 --> 02:24:13.560
[Amit Varma]: expert of sorts also, just has the process of reporting on something for so long, which such

02:24:13.560 --> 02:24:20.440
[Amit Varma]: depth enhanced your understanding of the subject, kind of massively. What I definitely feel it has

02:24:20.440 --> 02:24:29.320
[Guest]: done is expose me to a much wider range of perspectives than would have come to me normally.

02:24:29.320 --> 02:24:35.960
[Guest]: Yes, I do think that some of the that you know, the complete cluelessness of the early days has

02:24:35.960 --> 02:24:43.880
[Guest]: been replaced with some baseline understanding. But this is the thing it's every day continues

02:24:43.880 --> 02:24:50.680
[Guest]: to bring in very key fundamental, not esoteric aspects of it at all very key fundamental parts

02:24:50.680 --> 02:24:59.400
[Guest]: that I have no, not the slightest answer to, to the point that when I begin by asking the question,

02:24:59.400 --> 02:25:05.240
[Guest]: it's I'm really not being cute. I actually don't know. So for example, right now, if you know,

02:25:05.240 --> 02:25:10.280
[Guest]: if I would like to fashion myself as some sort of expert now, I should be able to say in at least

02:25:10.280 --> 02:25:16.680
[Guest]: one line, why have the cases started reducing from mid September. And because I haven't worked

02:25:16.680 --> 02:25:22.600
[Guest]: on it for an episode, I have no clue, I wouldn't be able to answer it in a single word. I have not

02:25:22.600 --> 02:25:31.640
[Guest]: one word of explanation for why this is. So no, I would only feel that I'm able to say much more

02:25:31.640 --> 02:25:37.960
[Guest]: about the things that I have looked at. But I don't feel any closer to feeling that I understand.

02:25:37.960 --> 02:25:43.240
[Guest]: And I don't understand why it's spread more widely in some places than others. I haven't

02:25:43.240 --> 02:25:47.640
[Guest]: seen convincing explanations for the most basic things. And this is one more thing where we,

02:25:47.640 --> 02:25:53.800
[Guest]: you know, you, I, I would come back to journalism, regular sort of mainstream journalism,

02:25:53.800 --> 02:26:00.520
[Guest]: which is how, how is it that I haven't in any news publication yet seen, forget an answer,

02:26:00.520 --> 02:26:08.200
[Guest]: at least an attempt at answering. Why did Pune have so many cases? I mean, why did Pune district

02:26:08.200 --> 02:26:13.720
[Guest]: have like four and a half thousand cases per day at a point? Why did Pune city have over 2000 cases

02:26:13.720 --> 02:26:19.560
[Guest]: for so many days? There's no good, you know, forget good explanation. I can't see anything

02:26:19.560 --> 02:26:26.440
[Guest]: that got anywhere near answering that. Then why did Punjab have such incredibly high mortality

02:26:26.440 --> 02:26:31.320
[Guest]: for a period? And, you know, the numbers in Punjab are still not numbers I properly understand.

02:26:31.320 --> 02:26:36.920
[Guest]: And then again, the news reporting says things like rumors spread on WhatsApp about,

02:26:36.920 --> 02:26:42.200
[Guest]: you know, treatments or some rumors spread on WhatsApp everywhere in the country. There's no

02:26:42.200 --> 02:26:48.840
[Guest]: way to understand why in particular in Punjab, this is what happened. Why are Bihar's numbers

02:26:48.840 --> 02:26:56.760
[Guest]: so low? I mean, it has to go beyond just a low population density because that, so, you know,

02:26:56.760 --> 02:27:02.840
[Guest]: no one has, this is, I just don't know if people are going in with clearly questioning minds,

02:27:02.840 --> 02:27:08.360
[Guest]: because if you can start with a position of humility, of accepting that there is a big

02:27:08.360 --> 02:27:13.160
[Guest]: central question that you have no idea what the answer to it is, maybe that would help you

02:27:13.160 --> 02:27:20.440
[Guest]: A, frame questions that people actually want the answers to, and then B, get any closer to

02:27:20.440 --> 02:27:25.640
[Guest]: answering them, rather than regurgitating what some expert panel is saying. So, there is some

02:27:25.640 --> 02:27:29.880
[Guest]: government expert panel that's saying, you know, this September was a peak and things will taper

02:27:29.880 --> 02:27:38.440
[Guest]: off by Feb, but no convincing explanation of why this has happened now. So, yeah, I don't feel

02:27:38.440 --> 02:27:46.440
[Guest]: I don't feel at all able to answer those things. And I don't see the attempt to answering it,

02:27:47.400 --> 02:27:51.000
[Guest]: attempt to getting to those questions more widely as well.

02:27:51.000 --> 02:27:54.520
[Amit Varma]: Well, I mean, one of the sort of things that struck me and impressed me while going through

02:27:54.520 --> 02:28:01.640
[Amit Varma]: the full series was not necessarily, you know, even if you don't listen to the episodes,

02:28:01.640 --> 02:28:05.560
[Amit Varma]: even if you just go to the medium page, and you look at the question that's been asked for

02:28:05.560 --> 02:28:11.720
[Amit Varma]: every episode, I think so much of our quest for the truth really comes from asking good questions,

02:28:11.720 --> 02:28:16.920
[Amit Varma]: which we don't see enough of. And, you know, you've asked, you know, almost every episode

02:28:16.920 --> 02:28:22.200
[Amit Varma]: has interesting questions, like Episode 71, what does the lockdowns, disruption and health services

02:28:22.200 --> 02:28:27.240
[Amit Varma]: mean for the health of Indians now in general? 72, what is it like to deal with COVID-19 in

02:28:27.240 --> 02:28:34.280
[Amit Varma]: rural India? 44, where does COVID fit into India's disease landscape? On Labor Day, you know, in

02:28:34.280 --> 02:28:39.720
[Amit Varma]: Episode 38, you asked, what is the future for work and workers? You know, what would life after the

02:28:39.720 --> 02:28:45.240
[Amit Varma]: lockdown look like? And it seems to me that just the act of being able to frame these questions

02:28:45.240 --> 02:28:50.600
[Amit Varma]: comes from a sort of a position of insight, you know, I've taken enough of your time,

02:28:50.600 --> 02:28:54.600
[Amit Varma]: and I don't want you to actually answer any of these questions here, because I would rather that

02:28:54.600 --> 02:28:59.800
[Amit Varma]: listeners go and listen to all those episodes, sort of like Rukmini said at the start, it's like

02:28:59.800 --> 02:29:04.760
[Amit Varma]: T20 matches, you know, five minute episodes, six minute episodes. And I don't say that disparagingly,

02:29:04.760 --> 02:29:10.840
[Amit Varma]: I'm just, I'm just full of enormous envy that, you know, one can pack in so much insight into

02:29:10.840 --> 02:29:16.600
[Amit Varma]: that kind of space. So I'll probably end with a couple of questions. And, you know, my penultimate

02:29:16.600 --> 02:29:20.840
[Amit Varma]: question really comes from, I guess, my self interest and the self interest of all of

02:29:21.400 --> 02:29:26.360
[Amit Varma]: the listeners who are still sort of struggling to cope with COVID in this difficult year.

02:29:26.360 --> 02:29:32.040
[Amit Varma]: And that comes from a question that you in fact, asked in episode 66, where you asked,

02:29:32.040 --> 02:29:36.840
[Amit Varma]: how do we measure the risk to ourselves? And this strikes me as an important question to ask,

02:29:36.840 --> 02:29:41.320
[Amit Varma]: because what we often see is a kind of pandemic fatigue has set in a lockdown fatigue, where

02:29:41.320 --> 02:29:45.640
[Amit Varma]: people are like, just screw it, you know, it's fine. And, you know, all of that, and

02:29:46.760 --> 02:29:51.000
[Amit Varma]: maybe people doing things they shouldn't do. But at the same time, you know, one can't blame them,

02:29:51.000 --> 02:29:56.280
[Amit Varma]: it's just horrible to live with this discipline and wear masks all the time and all of that.

02:29:56.280 --> 02:29:59.640
[Amit Varma]: What is your sense? How would you advise people on

02:29:59.640 --> 02:30:03.480
[Amit Varma]: how to sort of navigate the road ahead in the months to come?

02:30:04.840 --> 02:30:07.240
[Guest]: So I wouldn't like to think of this as advice, but

02:30:08.680 --> 02:30:14.280
[Guest]: more sort of what I feel I've heard, that makes more sense and is most convincing for me.

02:30:15.080 --> 02:30:23.480
[Guest]: So, you know, intimate, closed, mixed age events seem like a terrible idea.

02:30:23.480 --> 02:30:28.440
[Guest]: You know, research has shown this across the world and in India as well.

02:30:28.440 --> 02:30:36.920
[Guest]: Long shared transport is also a bad idea, though with the level of masking compliance that,

02:30:36.920 --> 02:30:41.240
[Guest]: you know, flights require, that might need to be recalibrated for that.

02:30:41.880 --> 02:30:47.480
[Guest]: But the thing is, what remains is, because there are so many unknowables,

02:30:47.480 --> 02:30:52.520
[Guest]: it's hard to understand what it is exactly that shakes some of these broad trends.

02:30:52.520 --> 02:30:55.800
[Guest]: So what suddenly causes, you know,

02:30:55.800 --> 02:31:00.600
[Guest]: deaths among younger people without comorbidities is impossible to say.

02:31:01.240 --> 02:31:06.120
[Guest]: You know, there was a period of time where young children were experiencing an inflammatory

02:31:06.120 --> 02:31:15.720
[Guest]: condition sort of associated with SARS-CoV-2, even though it wasn't directly that.

02:31:15.720 --> 02:31:22.600
[Guest]: So it's hard to say what those characteristics of those kids were and who were facing that.

02:31:22.600 --> 02:31:26.920
[Guest]: I suppose what I've taken broadly away for myself is as much as possible,

02:31:27.960 --> 02:31:32.600
[Guest]: whatever my privilege allows me to continue avoiding, I am continuing avoiding.

02:31:32.600 --> 02:31:37.720
[Guest]: So for example, I know everyone with little kids is, or even older kids who aren't going

02:31:37.720 --> 02:31:42.440
[Guest]: to school now is being driven up the wall now, having done this and homeschooling.

02:31:42.440 --> 02:31:47.080
[Guest]: But whoever's privilege allows them to continue keeping children at home,

02:31:47.800 --> 02:31:50.040
[Guest]: it seems to me like a good idea to do that.

02:31:50.040 --> 02:31:54.920
[Guest]: Now, recent research is showing just how much spreading happens

02:31:54.920 --> 02:31:59.640
[Guest]: among children and among intergenerational cohorts that include children as well.

02:31:59.640 --> 02:32:02.440
[Guest]: It's something we need to take more seriously in India, especially.

02:32:03.240 --> 02:32:06.120
[Guest]: You know, anyone who can continue working from home,

02:32:06.120 --> 02:32:10.040
[Guest]: all of those seem like things to continue to try to do.

02:32:10.040 --> 02:32:12.680
[Guest]: But, you know, I want to be very mindful, not just of

02:32:13.320 --> 02:32:17.640
[Guest]: work and money-related privileges, but also mental health, right?

02:32:17.640 --> 02:32:23.160
[Guest]: I mean, it's hard to advise these things to people struggling without

02:32:23.160 --> 02:32:26.360
[Guest]: other people to talk to, without other outlets, maybe even safety.

02:32:27.000 --> 02:32:29.160
[Guest]: So I think everyone is trying to build

02:32:30.200 --> 02:32:35.240
[Guest]: matrices of what they can avoid and what they must do.

02:32:35.880 --> 02:32:39.800
[Guest]: And, you know, these are going to be deeply personal things for most people.

02:32:39.800 --> 02:32:44.280
[Guest]: But, you know, the broad things of closed indoor events,

02:32:45.240 --> 02:32:52.040
[Guest]: any sort of, you know, large mass gatherings, of course, masking, you know.

02:32:52.040 --> 02:32:54.600
[Guest]: Though I have to say what frustrates me is that

02:32:54.600 --> 02:33:01.000
[Guest]: I still not seen proper research about cotton masks, the sort that we're all using.

02:33:01.000 --> 02:33:03.480
[Guest]: I know that there was simulation, which was, you know,

02:33:03.480 --> 02:33:06.040
[Guest]: the sort of when the advice was put out.

02:33:06.040 --> 02:33:12.200
[Guest]: But, yeah, I'm an absolutely passionate mask user and my little children use them as well.

02:33:12.200 --> 02:33:15.560
[Guest]: So I don't mean that I haven't seen anything to convince me.

02:33:15.560 --> 02:33:16.680
[Guest]: I'm completely convinced.

02:33:16.680 --> 02:33:22.600
[Guest]: I'm just saying that I would love to see a great research paper around it by now.

02:33:22.600 --> 02:33:26.040
[Guest]: So, yeah, these are the decisions I'm taking to just continue.

02:33:26.040 --> 02:33:27.960
[Guest]: My life has not really changed that much.

02:33:27.960 --> 02:33:33.320
[Guest]: Even since the lockdown, I still don't go out that much because as much as I can,

02:33:33.320 --> 02:33:38.520
[Guest]: you know, part of reporting on all of this is not just feeling that feeling terrible

02:33:38.520 --> 02:33:43.240
[Guest]: for the people who weren't able to continue staying in and, you know,

02:33:43.240 --> 02:33:46.040
[Guest]: realizing your enormous privilege in that.

02:33:46.040 --> 02:33:50.760
[Guest]: And to be very, to be, to remain humble in the face of this virus,

02:33:50.760 --> 02:33:57.400
[Guest]: to not feel that there are ways to be, you know, to not feel that youth

02:33:58.280 --> 02:34:01.480
[Guest]: or any of these sort of guarantees against it.

02:34:01.480 --> 02:34:05.400
[Guest]: I remain extremely humble in the face of the virus.

02:34:06.040 --> 02:34:06.920
[Amit Varma]: Very wise words.

02:34:06.920 --> 02:34:11.400
[Amit Varma]: And now my final question, which is, you know, almost a bit of a cliche to my listeners,

02:34:11.400 --> 02:34:12.680
[Amit Varma]: I think, but I have to ask it.

02:34:12.680 --> 02:34:17.400
[Amit Varma]: And especially in your sense, since, you know, your amazing journalism has given you such,

02:34:18.040 --> 02:34:22.440
[Amit Varma]: or at least has caused you to think so deeply about our democracy and our society.

02:34:22.440 --> 02:34:29.960
[Amit Varma]: If I ask you to, say, look ahead to 2030, away from this cursed year 2020 and look ahead to 2030,

02:34:29.960 --> 02:34:34.680
[Amit Varma]: what gives you hope and what gives you despair about what our country, our society,

02:34:34.680 --> 02:34:39.000
[Amit Varma]: our democracy is going through and could go through in this time?

02:34:39.960 --> 02:34:41.800
[Guest]: I see this, I hope it remains true.

02:34:41.800 --> 02:34:47.160
[Guest]: So what gives me hope is that I see enormous transformational power

02:34:47.960 --> 02:34:50.120
[Guest]: among people who fall in love.

02:34:50.120 --> 02:34:57.160
[Guest]: It amazes me the, I mean, first of all, the amount of love I see around,

02:34:57.160 --> 02:35:02.920
[Guest]: and I mean this in a sort of, you know, romantic love among young people.

02:35:02.920 --> 02:35:04.680
[Guest]: That's sort of, it's incredible.

02:35:04.680 --> 02:35:07.960
[Guest]: I mean, people are on the phone with each other all the time and finding places.

02:35:08.520 --> 02:35:14.520
[Guest]: And the power to take radical decisions around being in love is really quite something.

02:35:14.520 --> 02:35:16.520
[Guest]: I see it quite a bit.

02:35:16.520 --> 02:35:18.280
[Guest]: I hope it continues to grow.

02:35:18.280 --> 02:35:22.760
[Guest]: And the strength in that is something else.

02:35:22.760 --> 02:35:29.000
[Guest]: So it's one of the few things that gives me, it gives me hope that people will take,

02:35:29.000 --> 02:35:34.760
[Guest]: that young people will take otherwise enormous leaps that they might not have planned to,

02:35:35.720 --> 02:35:38.120
[Guest]: just out of being in love.

02:35:38.120 --> 02:35:43.000
[Guest]: So that's my extremely strange, you know, that's something that gives me hope.

02:35:43.000 --> 02:35:44.760
[Guest]: I see it a lot around me.

02:35:44.760 --> 02:35:47.160
[Guest]: And when people tell me, you know, I don't know,

02:35:47.160 --> 02:35:51.240
[Guest]: some people want to tell you, when they know that you've had a love marriage,

02:35:51.240 --> 02:35:53.880
[Guest]: people want to tell you their stories very often.

02:35:53.880 --> 02:35:56.440
[Guest]: And the things that people tell you about, you know,

02:35:56.440 --> 02:35:59.160
[Guest]: leaving home and just getting into a bus with no money.

02:35:59.160 --> 02:36:01.800
[Guest]: And it's just, it's amazing.

02:36:01.800 --> 02:36:04.600
[Guest]: It's so brave and it's very, it's something else.

02:36:06.200 --> 02:36:07.240
[Guest]: So that gives me hope.

02:36:07.240 --> 02:36:11.560
[Guest]: And the immense self-respect and pride that young people have,

02:36:11.560 --> 02:36:16.840
[Guest]: much more than every generation, increasingly so, gives me hope.

02:36:16.840 --> 02:36:22.120
[Guest]: What fills me with despair is, I think, conservatism among young people,

02:36:22.120 --> 02:36:23.960
[Guest]: again, is what fills me with despair.

02:36:23.960 --> 02:36:27.000
[Guest]: Conservatism among older people, less so.

02:36:27.880 --> 02:36:42.760
[Guest]: But, yeah, to hear, I can't currently see enough outlets and pushback against the sort of toxic

02:36:42.760 --> 02:36:45.640
[Guest]: Muslim hatred that is being pushed in most of the country.

02:36:45.640 --> 02:36:47.560
[Guest]: I can't see ways out of it right now.

02:36:48.120 --> 02:36:53.800
[Guest]: I don't see, I don't see like a big movement of young, anyone,

02:36:53.800 --> 02:36:57.640
[Guest]: of people strongly saying that this is a totally unacceptable thing.

02:36:57.640 --> 02:37:00.520
[Guest]: And, you know, we're going to put, really put our weight behind it.

02:37:00.520 --> 02:37:05.960
[Guest]: So, yeah, the Muslim hatred in this country is what gives me greatest despair.

02:37:06.600 --> 02:37:10.200
[Amit Varma]: Indeed. And, you know, we'll cycle back to the hope so we can end on a note of hope.

02:37:10.200 --> 02:37:13.960
[Amit Varma]: You are literally the first guest over, you know, 196 episodes,

02:37:13.960 --> 02:37:18.440
[Amit Varma]: who's spoken of romantic love as something that, you know, gives them hope.

02:37:18.440 --> 02:37:19.880
[Amit Varma]: And it's such a delightful answer.

02:37:19.880 --> 02:37:24.280
[Amit Varma]: And I'll sort of, you know, advise all my young listeners now that do not be conservative,

02:37:24.280 --> 02:37:27.560
[Amit Varma]: fall in love, but at the same time, don't get into a bus with no money.

02:37:27.560 --> 02:37:29.640
[Amit Varma]: That's not such a good idea.

02:37:29.640 --> 02:37:31.400
[Amit Varma]: I know it really well, so do it.

02:37:32.600 --> 02:37:34.520
[Amit Varma]: Okay, but wear a mask also.

02:37:34.520 --> 02:37:36.440
[Amit Varma]: Definitely don't get in without a mask.

02:37:37.320 --> 02:37:41.800
[Amit Varma]: Rukmini, thank you so much for being so patient with your time and so generous with your insights.

02:37:41.800 --> 02:37:43.000
[Amit Varma]: It was so amazing.

02:37:43.000 --> 02:37:47.560
[Amit Varma]: Having a podcaster like yourself, having a T20 star in a test match is so delightful.

02:37:48.760 --> 02:37:49.720
[Guest]: Thank you so much.

02:37:49.720 --> 02:37:50.760
[Guest]: A huge pleasure.

02:37:50.760 --> 02:37:52.360
[Guest]: And thank you to your listeners.

